But Runciter wouldn't admit it. Runciter and ubiquity.

3365
04:17:14,240 --> 04:17:20,720
Ubiquity, he realized all at once. That's the derivation of the made-up word, the name of Runciter's

3366
04:17:20,720 --> 04:17:27,280
alleged spray can product. Which probably did not even exist. It was probably a further hoax to

3367
04:17:27,280 --> 04:17:34,320
bewilder them that much more. And in addition, if Runciter were alive, then not one, but two

3368
04:17:34,320 --> 04:17:39,840
Runciter's existed. The genuine one in the real world who was striving to reach them,

3369
04:17:40,400 --> 04:17:45,360
and the phantasmagoric Runciter who had become a corpse in this half-life world,

3370
04:17:45,360 --> 04:17:52,160
the body lying in state in Des Moines, Iowa. And to carry the logic of this out to its full extent,

3371
04:17:52,160 --> 04:17:57,760
other persons here, such as Ray Hollis and Len Nigelman, were also phantasmagoria,

3372
04:17:58,400 --> 04:18:01,680
while their authentic counterparts remained in the world of the living.

3373
04:18:03,040 --> 04:18:08,880
Very confusing, Joe Chipp said to himself. He did not like it at all.

3374
04:18:09,840 --> 04:18:15,440
Granted, it had a satisfying symmetrical quality, but on the other hand, it struck him as untidy.

3375
04:18:16,400 --> 04:18:22,400
I'll zip over to my conapt. He decided to pick up the free sample of UBIC, then head for Des Moines.

3376
04:18:23,040 --> 04:18:28,720
After all, that's what the TV commercial urged me to do. I'll be safer carrying a can of UBIC

3377
04:18:28,720 --> 04:18:35,200
with me, as the ad pointed out in its own jingly, clever way. One has to pay attention to such

3378
04:18:35,200 --> 04:18:43,040
admonitions, he realized, if one expects to stay alive, or half alive, whichever it is.

3379
04:18:45,440 --> 04:18:50,880
Taxi let him off on the roof field of his conapt building. He descended by moving ramp and arrived

3380
04:18:50,880 --> 04:18:56,480
at his own door, with a coin that someone had given him, Al or Pat. He could not knowingly remember.

3381
04:18:56,480 --> 04:19:02,720
He opened the door and entered. The living room smelled faintly of burned grease, an odor he had

3382
04:19:02,720 --> 04:19:08,320
not come across since childhood. Going into the kitchen, he discovered the reason his stove had

3383
04:19:08,320 --> 04:19:14,720
reverted back to an ancient buck natural gas model, with clogged burners and encrusted oven door,

3384
04:19:14,720 --> 04:19:21,680
which did not close entirely. He gazed at the old, much used stove dully, then discovered that the

3385
04:19:21,680 --> 04:19:27,200
other kitchen appliances had undergone similar metamorphoses. The homeopaped machine had vanished

3386
04:19:27,200 --> 04:19:32,880
entirely. The toaster had dissolved sometime during the day and reformed itself as a rubbishy,

3387
04:19:32,880 --> 04:19:37,840
quaint, non-automatic model, not even pop-up, he discovered, as he poked bleakly at it.

3388
04:19:38,640 --> 04:19:43,760
The refrigerator that greeted him was an enormous, belt-driven model, a relic that had floated into

3389
04:19:43,760 --> 04:19:49,520
being from God knew what distant past. It was even more obsolete than the turret-top G.E.

3390
04:19:49,520 --> 04:19:55,440
shown in the TV commercial. The coffee-pot had undergone the least change. As a matter of fact,

3391
04:19:55,440 --> 04:20:00,480
in one respect, it had improved. It lacked the coin slot, operating obviously toll-free.

3392
04:20:01,200 --> 04:20:07,360
This aspect was true of all the appliances, he realized. All that remain, anyhow.

3393
04:20:07,920 --> 04:20:12,160
Like the homeopaped machine, the garbage disposal unit had entirely vanished.

3394
04:20:12,720 --> 04:20:18,320
He tried to remember what other appliances he had owned, but already memory had become vague.

3395
04:20:18,320 --> 04:20:24,800
He gave up and returned to the living-room. The TV set had receded back a long way.

3396
04:20:24,800 --> 04:20:30,320
He found himself confronted by a dark wood cabinet at Waterkent-tuned radio-frequency,

3397
04:20:30,320 --> 04:20:34,480
old-time AM radio, complete with antenna and ground wires.

3398
04:20:34,480 --> 04:20:40,880
God in heaven, he said to himself, appalled. But why hadn't the TV set reverted instead to

3399
04:20:40,880 --> 04:20:46,320
formless metals and plastics? Those, after all were its constituents,

3400
04:20:46,320 --> 04:20:53,840
it had been constructed out of them, not out of an earlier radio. Perhaps this weirdly verified

3401
04:20:53,840 --> 04:21:00,880
a discarded ancient philosophy that of Plato's ideal objects, the universals which in each class

3402
04:21:00,880 --> 04:21:08,000
were real. The form TV set had been a template imposed as a successor to other templates,

3403
04:21:08,000 --> 04:21:13,280
like the procession of frames in a movie sequence. Prior forms, he reflected, must

3404
04:21:13,280 --> 04:21:21,680
carry on an invisible residual life in every object. The past is latent, is submerged, but

3405
04:21:21,680 --> 04:21:27,840
still there, capable of rising to the surface once the later imprinting, unfortunately, and

3406
04:21:27,840 --> 04:21:36,960
against ordinary experience, vanished. The man contains not the boy, but earlier men, he thought.

3407
04:21:37,680 --> 04:21:45,280
History began a long time ago. The dehydrated remnants of Wendy, the procession of forms that

3408
04:21:45,280 --> 04:21:52,480
normally takes place, that procession ceased. And the last form wore off with nothing subsequent,

3409
04:21:52,480 --> 04:21:58,880
no newer form, no next stage of what we see as growth to take its place. This must be what we

3410
04:21:58,880 --> 04:22:06,320
experience as old age. From this absence comes degeneration and senility. Only in this instance,

3411
04:22:06,320 --> 04:22:13,040
it happened abruptly in a matter of hours. But this old theory didn't Plato think that

3412
04:22:13,040 --> 04:22:19,360
something survived the decline, something inner, not able to decay? The ancient dualism, body

3413
04:22:19,360 --> 04:22:25,600
separated from soul, the body ending, as Wendy did, and the soul out of its nest, the bird,

3414
04:22:25,600 --> 04:22:33,200
flown elsewhere. Maybe so, he thought. To be reborn again as the Tibetan book of the dead says,

3415
04:22:33,280 --> 04:22:40,960
it really is true. Christ, I hope so. Because in that case, we all can meet again. In, as in

3416
04:22:40,960 --> 04:22:46,320
Winnie the Pooh, another part of the forest, where a boy and his bear will always be playing,

3417
04:22:47,280 --> 04:22:54,240
a category he thought imperishable, like all of us. We will all wind up with Pooh in a clearer,

3418
04:22:54,240 --> 04:23:02,160
more durable new place. For curiosity's sake, he turned on the prehistoric radio set. The yellow

3419
04:23:02,160 --> 04:23:09,200
celluloid dial glowed. The set gave off a loud sixty-cycle hum, and then amid static and squeals,

3420
04:23:09,200 --> 04:23:15,680
a station came on. Time for Pepper Young's family, the announcer said, and organ music gurgled.

3421
04:23:16,240 --> 04:23:21,840
Brought to you by Myle Cammay, the soap of beautiful women. Yesterday, Pepper discovered

3422
04:23:21,840 --> 04:23:28,160
that the labor of months had come to an unexpected end due to the— Joe shut the radio off at that

3423
04:23:28,160 --> 04:23:34,720
point—a pre-World War II soap opera, he said to himself, marveling. Well, it followed the logic

3424
04:23:34,720 --> 04:23:40,880
of the former versions taking place in this, the dying half-world, or whatever it was.

3425
04:23:42,160 --> 04:23:47,040
Looking around the living room, he discovered a baroque-legged, glass-topped coffee table,

3426
04:23:47,040 --> 04:23:53,600
on which a copy of Liberty Magazine rested, also pre-World War II. The magazine featured a serial

3427
04:23:53,680 --> 04:24:00,320
entitled, Lightning in the Night, a Futuristic Fantasy Supposing an Atomic War. He turned the

3428
04:24:00,320 --> 04:24:06,560
pages numbly, then studied the room as a whole, seeking to identify other changes. The tough,

3429
04:24:06,560 --> 04:24:12,880
neutral-colored floor had become wide, softwood boards, in the center of the room a faded Turkish

3430
04:24:12,880 --> 04:24:19,280
rug lay impregnated with years of dust. One single picture remained on the wall,

3431
04:24:19,280 --> 04:24:24,880
a glass-covered frame print in monochrome showing a dying Indian on horseback. He had never seen

3432
04:24:24,880 --> 04:24:31,200
it before, it stirred no memories, and he did not care for it one bit. The vid-phone had been

3433
04:24:31,200 --> 04:24:37,040
replaced by a black hook-style upright telephone, pre-dial. He lifted the receiver from the hook

3434
04:24:37,040 --> 04:24:40,960
and heard a female voice saying, Hammer, please. At that he hung up.

3435
04:24:42,800 --> 04:24:48,400
The thermostatically controlled heating system had evidently departed. At one end of the living

3436
04:24:48,400 --> 04:24:54,080
room he perceived a gas heater, complete with large tin flue running up the wall almost to the

3437
04:24:54,080 --> 04:25:00,240
ceiling. Going into the bedroom he looked in the closet, rummage, then assembled an outfit. Black

3438
04:25:00,240 --> 04:25:06,000
oxfords, wool socks, knickers, blue cotton shirt, camel's hair, sports coat, and golf cap.

3439
04:25:06,720 --> 04:25:12,000
For more formal wear he laid out on the bed a pinstripe, blue-black double-breasted suit,

3440
04:25:12,000 --> 04:25:16,800
suspenders, wide floral necktie, and white shirt with celluloid collar.

3441
04:25:16,880 --> 04:25:22,800
Jeez, he said to himself in dismay, as in the closet he came across a golf bag with assorted

3442
04:25:22,800 --> 04:25:28,960
clubs. What a relic! Once more he returned to the living room. This time he noticed the spot where

3443
04:25:28,960 --> 04:25:34,480
his polyphonic audio components had formerly been assembled. The multiplex FM tuner, the high

3444
04:25:34,480 --> 04:25:40,320
hysteresis turntable and weightless tracking arm, speakers, horns, multi-track amplifier,

3445
04:25:40,320 --> 04:25:47,680
all had vanished. In their place a tall tan wooden structure greeted him. He made out the crank

3446
04:25:47,680 --> 04:25:53,760
handle and did not need to lift the lid to know what his sound system now consisted of. Bamboo

3447
04:25:53,760 --> 04:25:59,920
needles, a pack of them on the bookcase beside the Victrola, and a 10-inch 78-speed black label

3448
04:25:59,920 --> 04:26:05,920
Victor record of Ray Noble's orchestra playing Turkish delight. So much for his tape and LP

3449
04:26:06,000 --> 04:26:11,200
collection. And by tomorrow he would probably find himself equipped with a cylinder phonograph

3450
04:26:11,200 --> 04:26:16,240
screw-driven, and to play on it a shouted recitation of the Lord's Prayer.

3451
04:26:17,920 --> 04:26:23,120
A fresh-looking newspaper lying at the far end of the overstuffed sofa attracted his attention.

3452
04:26:23,120 --> 04:26:30,240
He picked it up and read the date. Tuesday, September 12, 1939. He scanned the headlines.

3453
04:26:30,880 --> 04:26:35,840
French claim Siegfried Line Dented report gains in area near Sarbrookin.

3454
04:26:35,840 --> 04:26:38,480
Major battle said to be shaping up along western front.

3455
04:26:39,520 --> 04:26:44,240
Interesting, he said to himself, World War II had just begun and the French thought they were

3456
04:26:44,240 --> 04:26:51,440
winning it. He read another headline. Polish report claims German forces halted. Say, invaders throw

3457
04:26:51,440 --> 04:26:57,840
new forces into battle without new gains. The newspaper had cost three cents. That

3458
04:26:57,920 --> 04:27:02,480
interested him, too. What could you get now for three cents, he asked himself.

3459
04:27:03,040 --> 04:27:08,080
He tossed the newspaper back down and marveled once again at its freshness, a day or so old,

3460
04:27:08,080 --> 04:27:15,280
he guessed. No more than that. So I now have a time-fix. I know precisely how far back the regression

3461
04:27:15,280 --> 04:27:20,720
has carried. Wandering about the con app, searching out the various changes, he found

3462
04:27:20,720 --> 04:27:26,480
himself facing a chest of dresser drawers in the bedroom. On the top rested several framed glass

3463
04:27:26,480 --> 04:27:34,960
covered photographs. All were of Runceter. But not the Runceter he knew. These were of a baby,

3464
04:27:34,960 --> 04:27:40,560
a small boy, then a young man. Runceter, as he had once been, but still recognizable.

3465
04:27:41,200 --> 04:27:46,480
Getting out his wallet, he found only snapshots of Runceter. None of his family, none of friends,

3466
04:27:46,480 --> 04:27:52,880
Runceter, everywhere. He returned the wallet to his pocket, then realized with a jolt that it had

3467
04:27:52,880 --> 04:27:59,440
been made of natural cowhide, not plastic. Well, that fitted. In the old days there had been organic

3468
04:27:59,440 --> 04:28:05,760
leather available. So what, he said to himself, bringing the wallet out once more, he somberly

3469
04:28:05,760 --> 04:28:13,280
scrutinized it. He rubbed the cowhide and experienced a new tactile sensation, a pleasant one,

3470
04:28:13,280 --> 04:28:19,440
infinitely superior to plastic, he decided. Back in the living room again he poked about searching

3471
04:28:19,440 --> 04:28:24,720
for the familiar mail slot, the recessed wall cavity, which should have contained today's mail.

3472
04:28:24,720 --> 04:28:31,840
It had vanished. It no longer existed. He pondered, trying to envision old-time mail practices

3473
04:28:32,640 --> 04:28:42,000
on the floor outside the con-app door. No. In a box of some kind. He recalled the term mail box.

3474
04:28:42,880 --> 04:28:49,360
Okay, it would be in the mail box. But where had mail boxes been located? At the main entrance

3475
04:28:49,440 --> 04:28:56,160
of the building? That dimly seemed right. He would have to leave his con-app. The mail would be found

3476
04:28:56,160 --> 04:29:02,800
on the ground floor twenty stories below. Five cents, please, his front door said when he tried to open it.

3477
04:29:03,760 --> 04:29:09,840
One thing anyhow hadn't changed. The toll door had an innate stubbornness to it. Probably it

3478
04:29:09,840 --> 04:29:15,040
would hold out after everything else. After everything except it had long since reverted,

3479
04:29:15,120 --> 04:29:19,600
perhaps in the whole city, if not the whole world. He paid the door a nickel,

3480
04:29:19,600 --> 04:29:22,960
hurried down the hall to the moving ramp which he had used only minutes ago.

3481
04:29:23,760 --> 04:29:28,240
The ramp, however, had now reverted to a flight of inert concrete stairs.

3482
04:29:28,960 --> 04:29:36,800
Twenty flights down, he reflected. Step by step. Impossible! No one could walk down that many

3483
04:29:36,800 --> 04:29:42,640
stairs. The elevator. He started toward it, then remembered what had happened to Al. Suppose this

3484
04:29:42,640 --> 04:29:48,720
time I see what he saw, he said to himself. An old iron cage hanging from a wire cable operated by

3485
04:29:48,720 --> 04:29:55,600
a senile borderline moron wearing an official elevator operator's cap. Not a vision of 1939,

3486
04:29:55,600 --> 04:30:00,960
but a vision of 1909. A regression much greater than anything I've run into so far.

3487
04:30:02,080 --> 04:30:07,280
Better not to risk it. Better to take the stairs. Resigned, he began to descend.

3488
04:30:08,000 --> 04:30:12,080
He had gotten almost halfway down when something ominous flicked alive in his brain.

3489
04:30:12,720 --> 04:30:18,240
There was no way by which he could get back up, either to his conapt or to the roof field where

3490
04:30:18,240 --> 04:30:23,120
the taxi waited. Once on the ground floor he would be confined there. Maybe forever.

3491
04:30:24,160 --> 04:30:28,480
Unless the spray can of Ubeck was potent enough to restore the elevator or the moving ramp.

3492
04:30:29,600 --> 04:30:35,680
Surface travel, he said to himself. What the hell will that consist of by the time I get down their

3493
04:30:35,680 --> 04:30:42,480
train? Covered wagon? Clattering down two steps at a time, he morosely continued his descent

3494
04:30:42,480 --> 04:30:48,160
too late now to change his mind. When he reached the ground level, he found himself confronted by

3495
04:30:48,160 --> 04:30:54,400
a large lobby, including a marble top table, very long, on which two ceramic vases of flowers,

3496
04:30:54,400 --> 04:31:01,600
evidently iris, rested. Four wide steps led down to the curtain front door. He grasped the faceted

3497
04:31:01,600 --> 04:31:07,840
glass knob of the door and swung it open. More steps, and on the right a row of locked brass

3498
04:31:07,840 --> 04:31:13,840
mailboxes, each with a name, each requiring a key. He had been right. This was as far as the mail was

3499
04:31:13,840 --> 04:31:19,040
brought. He located his own box, finding a strip of paper at the bottom of it, reading Joseph Chip,

3500
04:31:19,040 --> 04:31:24,720
2075, plus a button which, when pressed, evidently rang upstairs in his conapt.

3501
04:31:24,960 --> 04:31:33,600
The key. He had no key, or did he? Fishing in his pockets, he discovered a ring on which several

3502
04:31:33,600 --> 04:31:39,520
diversely shaped metal keys dangled. Perplexed, he studied them, wondering what they were for.

3503
04:31:40,480 --> 04:31:45,440
The lock on the mailbox seemed unusually small. Obviously, it took a similar size key.

3504
04:31:45,440 --> 04:31:50,960
Selecting the most meager key on the ring, he inserted it in the lock of the mailbox, turned it.

3505
04:31:51,040 --> 04:31:54,640
The brass door of the box fell open. He peered inside.

3506
04:31:55,840 --> 04:32:02,000
Within the box lay two letters, and a square package wrapped in brown paper sealed with brown tape.

3507
04:32:02,720 --> 04:32:09,440
Purple, three-cent stamps with a portrait of George Washington. He paused to admire these unusual

3508
04:32:09,440 --> 04:32:14,480
memorabilia from the past, and then, ignoring the letters, tore open the square package,

3509
04:32:14,480 --> 04:32:20,000
finding it rewardingly heavy. But he realized suddenly it's the wrong shape for a spray can.

3510
04:32:20,000 --> 04:32:25,600
It's not tall enough. Fear touched him. What if it was not a free sample of Ubeck?

3511
04:32:26,240 --> 04:32:30,720
It had to be. It just had to be. Otherwise, al, all over again.

3512
04:32:31,520 --> 04:32:36,640
Morserta et Horacerta, he said to himself, as he dropped the brown paper wrappings and

3513
04:32:36,640 --> 04:32:42,720
examined the paste-board container within. Ubeck, liver, and kidney bomb.

3514
04:32:43,680 --> 04:32:49,520
Inside the container, he found a blue glass jar with a large lid. The label read,

3515
04:32:49,520 --> 04:32:56,400
Directions for Use. This unique analgesic formula, developed over a period of 40 years by Dr.

3516
04:32:56,400 --> 04:33:02,640
Edward Sondbar, is guaranteed to end forever, annoying getting up at night. You will sleep

3517
04:33:02,640 --> 04:33:08,400
peacefully for the first time and with superlative comfort. Merely dissolve a teaspoonful of Ubeck

3518
04:33:08,400 --> 04:33:14,800
liver and kidney bomb in a glass of warm water and drink immediately one half hour before retiring.

3519
04:33:14,800 --> 04:33:22,000
If pain or irritation persists, increase dosage to one tablespoon full. Do not give to children.

3520
04:33:22,560 --> 04:33:26,320
Contains processed oleander leaves, salt, Peter, oil of peppermint,

3521
04:33:26,320 --> 04:33:32,480
enosetal, Pia minifinal, zinc oxide, charcoal, cobalt chloride, caffeine, extract of digitalis,

3522
04:33:32,480 --> 04:33:37,840
steroids and trace amounts, sodium citrate, ascorbic acid, artificial coloring and flavoring.

3523
04:33:38,480 --> 04:33:43,200
Ubeck liver and kidney bomb is potent and effective if handled as per instructions.

3524
04:33:43,200 --> 04:33:52,000
Imflammable. Use rubber gloves. Do not allow to get in eyes. Do not splash on skin. Do not

3525
04:33:52,000 --> 04:34:00,320
inhale over long periods of time. Warning. Prolonged or excessive use may result in habituation.

3526
04:34:01,040 --> 04:34:07,840
This is insane, Joe said to himself. He read the list of ingredients once more feeling growing

3527
04:34:07,840 --> 04:34:13,760
baffled anger and a mounting helpless sensation that took root and spread through every part of him.

3528
04:34:14,320 --> 04:34:20,080
I'm finished, he said to himself. This stuff isn't what Runciter advertised on TV. This is some

3529
04:34:20,080 --> 04:34:27,600
arcane mixture of old time patent medicine, skin salves, pain killers, poisons, inert nothings,

3530
04:34:28,240 --> 04:34:32,320
plus of all things cortisone, which didn't exist before World War II.

3531
04:34:33,280 --> 04:34:36,960
Obviously, the Ubeck which he described to me in the tape-TV commercial,

3532
04:34:37,520 --> 04:34:43,600
this sample of it anyhow, has reverted an irony that is just plain too much.

3533
04:34:43,600 --> 04:34:49,120
The substance created to reverse the regressive change process has itself regressed. I should

3534
04:34:49,120 --> 04:34:54,720
have known as soon as I saw the old purple three-cent stamps. He looked up and down the street

3535
04:34:54,720 --> 04:34:59,440
and saw parked at the curb a classic museum piece surface car, a LaSalle.

3536
04:34:59,440 --> 04:35:05,360
Can I get to Des Moines in a 1939 LaSalle automobile? he asked himself.

3537
04:35:06,400 --> 04:35:12,480
Eventually, if it remains stable, perhaps a week from now, but by then it won't matter,

3538
04:35:12,480 --> 04:35:17,600
and anyhow the car won't remain stable. Nothing, except maybe my front door will.

3539
04:35:18,800 --> 04:35:22,240
However, he walked over to the LaSalle to examine it at close range.

3540
04:35:23,200 --> 04:35:29,440
Maybe it's mine, he said to himself. Maybe one of my keys fits its ignition.

3541
04:35:29,440 --> 04:35:33,520
Isn't that how surface cars operate? On the other hand, how am I going to drive it? I don't

3542
04:35:33,520 --> 04:35:37,920
know how to pilot an old-time automobile, especially one with, what did they call it,

3543
04:35:38,720 --> 04:35:44,560
manual transmission. He opened the door and slid onto the seat behind the driver's steering wheel.

3544
04:35:45,280 --> 04:35:50,080
There he sat, plucking aimlessly at his lower lip and trying to think the situation through.

3545
04:35:51,040 --> 04:35:56,480
Maybe I ought to drink down a tablespoon of ubeck liver and kidney bomb, he said to himself,

3546
04:35:56,480 --> 04:36:02,800
grimly. With those ingredients it ought to kill me fairly thoroughly. But it did not strike him

3547
04:36:02,800 --> 04:36:09,440
as the kind of death he could welcome. The cobalt chloride would do it very slowly and agonizingly,

3548
04:36:09,440 --> 04:36:14,560
unless the digitalis managed it first. And there were, of course, the oleander leaves.

3549
04:36:14,560 --> 04:36:20,640
They could hardly be overlooked. The whole combination would melt his bones into jelly inch

3550
04:36:20,640 --> 04:36:30,400
by inch. Wait a minute, he thought. Air transportation existed in 1939. If I could get to the New York

3551
04:36:30,400 --> 04:36:38,720
Airport, possibly in this car, I could charter a flight. Rent a Ford tri-motor plane complete

3552
04:36:38,720 --> 04:36:45,200
with pilot, that would get me to Des Moines. He tried his various keys and, at last, found one which

3553
04:36:45,200 --> 04:36:50,640
switched on the car's ignition. The starter motor cranked away and then the engine caught. With a

3554
04:36:50,640 --> 04:36:57,040
healthy rumble, the engine continued to turn over and the sound of it pleased him. Like the genuine

3555
04:36:57,040 --> 04:37:03,280
cow-hide wallet, this particular regression struck him as an improvement. Being completely silent,

3556
04:37:03,280 --> 04:37:08,000
the transportation of his own time lacked this palpable touch of sturdy realism.

3557
04:37:08,880 --> 04:37:15,760
Now the clutch, he said to himself, over on the left, with his foot he located it. Clutch down to

3558
04:37:15,760 --> 04:37:24,000
the floor, then shift the lever into gear. He tried it and obtained a horrid clashing noise, metal

3559
04:37:24,000 --> 04:37:29,360
whirring against metal. Evidently he had managed to let up on the clutch. He tried it again. This

3560
04:37:29,360 --> 04:37:35,360
time he successfully got it into gear. Lurching, the car moved forward. It bucked and shuttered,

3561
04:37:35,360 --> 04:37:41,520
but it moved. It limped erratically up the street and he felt within him a certain measured renewal

3562
04:37:41,520 --> 04:37:47,280
of optimism. And now let's see if we can find the goddamn airfield, he said to himself, before

3563
04:37:47,280 --> 04:37:52,880
it's too late, before we're back in the days of the gnome rotary engine with its revolving outside

3564
04:37:52,880 --> 04:37:58,960
cylinders and its castor oil lubricant, good for fifty miles of hedge-hopping flight at seventy-five

3565
04:37:58,960 --> 04:38:05,120
miles per hour. An hour later he arrived at the airfield, parked and surveyed the hangars, the

3566
04:38:05,120 --> 04:38:11,120
windsock, the old bi-planes with their huge wooden props. What a sight, he reflected. An

3567
04:38:11,120 --> 04:38:17,360
indistinct page out of history. Recreated remnants of another millennium lacking any connection with

3568
04:38:17,360 --> 04:38:23,920
the familiar real world, a phantasm that had drifted into sight only momentarily, this too,

3569
04:38:23,920 --> 04:38:30,800
would be gone soon. It would no more survive than had contemporary artifacts. The process of

3570
04:38:30,800 --> 04:38:36,400
devolution would sweep this away like it had everything else. He got shakily from the LaSalle

3571
04:38:36,400 --> 04:38:40,960
feeling acutely carcid and trudged toward the main buildings of the airfield.

3572
04:38:41,040 --> 04:38:47,520
What can I charter with this, he asked, laying all his money out on the counter before the first

3573
04:38:47,520 --> 04:38:51,920
official-looking person he caught sight of. I want to get to Des Moines as quickly as possible.

3574
04:38:51,920 --> 04:38:58,560
I want to take off right away. The field official, bald-headed with a waxed mustache and small round

3575
04:38:58,560 --> 04:39:01,440
gold-rimmed eyeglasses, inspected the bill silently.

3576
04:39:02,640 --> 04:39:07,280
Hey, Sam! he called with a turn of his apple-like round head. Come here and look at this money.

3577
04:39:08,000 --> 04:39:12,720
A second individual, wearing a striped shirt with billowing sleeves, shiny seersucker trousers,

3578
04:39:12,720 --> 04:39:17,920
and canvas shoes, stumped over. Fake money, he said after he had taken his look.

3579
04:39:18,480 --> 04:39:24,000
Play money, not George Washington and not Alexander Hamilton. Both officials scrutinized Joe.

3580
04:39:25,120 --> 04:39:30,560
Joe said, I have a 39 LaSalle parked in the parking lot. I'll trade it for a one-way flight

3581
04:39:30,560 --> 04:39:33,600
to Des Moines on any plane that'll get me there. Does that interest you?

3582
04:39:33,680 --> 04:39:38,800
Presently the official with the little gold-rimmed glasses said meditatively,

3583
04:39:39,440 --> 04:39:44,880
maybe Augie Brent would be interested. Brent, the official in the seersucker pants said,

3584
04:39:44,880 --> 04:39:49,680
raising his eyebrows. You mean that Jenny of his that plane's over 20 years old wouldn't get to

3585
04:39:49,680 --> 04:39:56,800
Philadelphia. How about McGee? Sure, but he's in Newark. Then maybe Sandy Jesperson. That Curtis

3586
04:39:56,800 --> 04:40:02,400
right of his would make it to Iowa. Sooner or later. To Joe, the official said, go out by

3587
04:40:02,400 --> 04:40:06,880
Hangar 3 and look for a red-and-white Curtis biplane. You'll see a little short guy sort of fat

3588
04:40:06,880 --> 04:40:11,040
fiddling around with it. If he doesn't take you up on it, nobody here will, unless you want to

3589
04:40:11,040 --> 04:40:17,120
wait till tomorrow for Ike McGee to come back here in his Focker trimotor. Thanks, Joe said.

3590
04:40:17,120 --> 04:40:22,160
And left the building. He strode rapidly toward Hangar 3, already seeing what looked like a

3591
04:40:22,160 --> 04:40:27,200
red-and-white Curtis right biplane. At least I won't be making the trip in a World War J. N.

3592
04:40:27,200 --> 04:40:30,080
Training plane, he said to himself. And then he thought,

3593
04:40:30,880 --> 04:40:34,560
how did I know that Jenny is a nickname for a J. N. Trainer?

3594
04:40:35,520 --> 04:40:40,960
Good God, he thought. Elements of this period appear to be developing corresponding coordinates

3595
04:40:40,960 --> 04:40:46,240
in my mind. No wonder I was able to drive the Lissalle. I'm beginning to phase mentally with

3596
04:40:46,240 --> 04:40:52,400
this time continuum in earnest. A short fat man with red hair puttered with an oily rag at the

3597
04:40:52,400 --> 04:40:55,520
wheels of his biplane. He glanced up as Joe approached.

3598
04:40:56,240 --> 04:40:58,400
Are you Mr. Jesperson? Joe asked.

3599
04:40:58,960 --> 04:41:04,720
That's right. The man surveyed him, obviously mystified by Joe's clothes, which had not reverted.

3600
04:41:04,720 --> 04:41:07,040
What can I do for you? Joe told him.

3601
04:41:07,680 --> 04:41:12,720
You want to trade a Lissalle? A new Lissalle for a one-way trip to Des Moines?

3602
04:41:12,720 --> 04:41:18,560
Jesperson cogitated his brows knitting. Might as well be both ways. I gotta fly back here anyway.

3603
04:41:19,520 --> 04:41:23,600
Okay, I'll take a look at it. But I'm not promising anything. I haven't made up my mind.

3604
04:41:24,480 --> 04:41:26,480
Together they made their way to the parking lot.

3605
04:41:27,040 --> 04:41:32,720
I don't see any 39 Lissalle, Jesperson said suspiciously. The man was right, the Lissalle

3606
04:41:32,720 --> 04:41:39,920
had disappeared. In its place, Joe saw a fabric top Ford Coupe, a tinny and small car, very old,

3607
04:41:39,920 --> 04:41:48,000
1929, he guessed. A black 1929 model A Ford, nearly worthless, he could tell that from Jesperson's

3608
04:41:48,000 --> 04:41:54,720
expression. Obviously it was now hopeless. He would never get to Des Moines. And as Runceter

3609
04:41:54,720 --> 04:42:01,360
had pointed out in his TV commercial, this meant death. The same death that had overtaken Wendy and

3610
04:42:01,360 --> 04:42:09,280
Al. It would be only a matter of time. Better he thought to die another way. You, Bick, he thought.

3611
04:42:09,840 --> 04:42:15,520
He opened the door of his Ford and got in. There on the seat beside him rested the bottle, which

3612
04:42:15,520 --> 04:42:22,000
he had received in the mail. He picked it up and discovered something which did not really surprise

3613
04:42:22,000 --> 04:42:30,320
him. The bottle, like the car, had again regressed. Seamless and flat with scratch marks on it.

3614
04:42:30,320 --> 04:42:37,200
The kind of bottle made in a wooden mold, very old indeed. The cap appeared to be handmade.

3615
04:42:37,200 --> 04:42:43,520
A soft tin screw type, dating from the late 19th century. The label too had changed. Holding the

3616
04:42:43,520 --> 04:42:49,600
bottle up, he read the words printed on it. Elixir of Eubick guaranteed to restore lost manliness

3617
04:42:49,600 --> 04:42:55,520
and to banish vapors of all known kinds, as well as to relieve reproductive complaints in both men

3618
04:42:55,520 --> 04:43:04,000
and women. A beneficent aid to mankind when sedulously employed as indicated. And, in smaller

3619
04:43:04,000 --> 04:43:09,520
type, a further inscription he had to squint in order to read the smudged, minute script.

3620
04:43:10,480 --> 04:43:17,200
Don't do it, Joe. There's another way. Keep trying. You'll find it. Lots of luck.

3621
04:43:18,720 --> 04:43:24,160
Ranseter, he realized. Still playing his sadistic cat and mouse games with us,

3622
04:43:24,160 --> 04:43:30,000
goading us into keeping going a little longer, delaying the end as long as possible. God knows why.

3623
04:43:31,120 --> 04:43:36,560
Maybe he thought Ranseter enjoys our torment. But that isn't like him. That's not the Glenn

3624
04:43:36,560 --> 04:43:43,360
Ranseter I knew. However, Joe put the elixir of Eubick bottled down, abandoning the idea of making

3625
04:43:43,360 --> 04:43:50,080
use of it, and wondered what Ranseter's elusive hinted at other way might be.

3626
04:43:53,520 --> 04:43:54,000
11.

3627
04:43:55,920 --> 04:44:00,880
Taken as directed, Eubick provides uninterrupted sleep without mourning after groggyness. You

3628
04:44:00,960 --> 04:44:07,520
awaken fresh, ready to tackle all those little annoying problems facing you. Do not exceed

3629
04:44:07,520 --> 04:44:08,800
recommended dosage.

3630
04:44:10,400 --> 04:44:15,920
Hey, that bottle you have, Jesperson said. He peered into the car, an unusual note in his voice.

3631
04:44:16,720 --> 04:44:22,320
Can I look at it? Joe Chip wordlessly passed the aviator the flat bottle of elixir of Eubick.

3632
04:44:23,040 --> 04:44:28,000
My grandmother used to talk about this, Jesperson said, holding the bottle up to the light.

3633
04:44:28,000 --> 04:44:31,680
Would you get it? They haven't made this since around the time of the Civil War.

3634
04:44:32,560 --> 04:44:39,360
I inherited it, Joe said. You must have. Yeah, you don't see these handmade flasks anymore.

3635
04:44:39,360 --> 04:44:43,920
The company never put out very many of these in the first place. This medicine was invented in

3636
04:44:43,920 --> 04:44:49,600
San Francisco around 1850. Never sold in stores. The customers had to order it made up. It came

3637
04:44:49,600 --> 04:44:54,960
in three strains. This, what you have here, this is the strongest of the three. The I, Joe.

3638
04:44:55,840 --> 04:44:56,640
Do you know what's in this?

3639
04:44:57,600 --> 04:45:03,760
Sure, Joe said. Oil of peppermint, zinc oxide, sodium citrate, charcoal. Let it go,

3640
04:45:03,760 --> 04:45:09,120
Jesperson interrupted. Frowning, he appeared to be busily turning something over in his mind.

3641
04:45:09,120 --> 04:45:12,320
Then, at last, his expression changed. He had come to a decision.

3642
04:45:13,280 --> 04:45:17,600
I'll fly you to Des Moines in exchange for this flask of elixir of Eubick.

3643
04:45:17,600 --> 04:45:20,560
Let's get started. I want to do as much of the flying as possible in daylight.

3644
04:45:21,120 --> 04:45:24,080
He strode away from the twenty-nine-four, taking the bottle with him.

3645
04:45:24,080 --> 04:45:30,240
Ten minutes later the Curtis Rye biplane had been gassed, the prop manually spun,

3646
04:45:30,240 --> 04:45:36,880
and with Joe Chip and Jesperson aboard, it began weaving an erratic, sloppy path down the runway.

3647
04:45:36,880 --> 04:45:41,360
Bouncing into the air and then collapsing back again, Joe gritted his teeth and hung on.

3648
04:45:41,920 --> 04:45:47,040
We're carrying so much weight, Jesperson said without emotion. He did not seem alarmed.

3649
04:45:47,600 --> 04:45:52,080
The plane at last wobbled up into the air, leaving the runway permanently behind.

3650
04:45:52,560 --> 04:45:56,720
Noisily, it droned over the rooftops of buildings on its way west.

3651
04:45:57,600 --> 04:46:00,480
Joe yelled, How long will it take to get there?

3652
04:46:01,120 --> 04:46:07,200
Depends on how much tailwind we get. Hard to say. Probably around noon tomorrow, if our luck holds

3653
04:46:07,200 --> 04:46:11,600
out. Will you tell me now, Joe yelled, What's in the bottle?

3654
04:46:12,560 --> 04:46:18,000
Gold flakes suspended in a base composed mostly of mineral oil, the pilot yelled back.

3655
04:46:18,880 --> 04:46:20,560
How much gold? Very much!

3656
04:46:21,520 --> 04:46:26,800
Jesperson turned his head and grinned without answering. He did not have to say. It was obvious.

3657
04:46:27,360 --> 04:46:32,320
The old Curtis Rye biplane blurbled on in the general direction of Iowa.

3658
04:46:34,160 --> 04:46:38,400
At three in the afternoon the following day they reached the airfield at Des Moines.

3659
04:46:38,400 --> 04:46:41,920
Having landed the plane, the pilot sauntered off for parts unknown,

3660
04:46:41,920 --> 04:46:46,960
carrying his flask of gold flakes with him. With aching, cramped stiffness,

3661
04:46:46,960 --> 04:46:51,520
Joe climbed from the plane, stood for a time rubbing his numb legs,

3662
04:46:51,520 --> 04:46:56,400
and then unsteadily headed toward the airport office, as little of it as there was.

3663
04:46:57,440 --> 04:47:01,760
Can I use your phone? he asked an elderly rustic official who sat hunched over a

3664
04:47:01,760 --> 04:47:03,760
weather map absorbed in what he was doing.

3665
04:47:04,560 --> 04:47:09,840
If you got a nickel, the official, with a jerk of his cowlick head, indicated the public phone.

3666
04:47:10,640 --> 04:47:15,760
Joe sorted through his money, casting out all the coins which had Runciter's profile on them.

3667
04:47:16,320 --> 04:47:20,960
At last he found an authentic buffalo nickel of the period and laid it before the elderly official.

3668
04:47:22,560 --> 04:47:24,560
The official grunted without looking up.

3669
04:47:25,600 --> 04:47:30,880
Locating the local phone book, Joe extracted from it the number of the simple shepherd mortuary.

3670
04:47:30,880 --> 04:47:34,320
He gave the number to the operator and presently his party responded.

3671
04:47:35,360 --> 04:47:38,640
Simple shepherd mortuary? Mr. Bliss speaking.

3672
04:47:39,520 --> 04:47:44,240
I'm here to attend the services for Glen Runciter, Joe said. Am I too late?

3673
04:47:44,240 --> 04:47:46,080
He prayed silently that he was not.

3674
04:47:46,960 --> 04:47:50,960
Services for Mr. Runciter are in progress right now, Mr. Bliss said.

3675
04:47:52,160 --> 04:47:56,160
Where are you, sir? Would you like us to send a vehicle to fetch you?

3676
04:47:56,160 --> 04:47:58,080
He seemed fussily disapproving.

3677
04:47:58,640 --> 04:48:00,480
I'm at the airport, Joe said.

3678
04:48:00,480 --> 04:48:03,680
You should have arrived earlier, Mr. Bliss chided.

3679
04:48:03,680 --> 04:48:06,400
I doubt very much if you'll be able to attend any of the service.

3680
04:48:07,200 --> 04:48:12,160
However, Mr. Runciter will be lying in state for the balance of today and tomorrow morning.

3681
04:48:12,160 --> 04:48:14,160
Watch for our car, Mr.—

3682
04:48:15,040 --> 04:48:16,080
Chip, Joe said.

3683
04:48:16,800 --> 04:48:19,280
Yes, you have been expected.

3684
04:48:19,280 --> 04:48:22,800
Several of the bereaved have asked that we maintain a vigil for you,

3685
04:48:22,800 --> 04:48:25,200
as well as for Mr. Hammond and a—

3686
04:48:26,160 --> 04:48:26,800
He paused.

3687
04:48:27,360 --> 04:48:29,280
A mis-right. Are they with you?

3688
04:48:30,320 --> 04:48:31,440
No, Joe said.

3689
04:48:32,080 --> 04:48:35,920
He hung up, then seated himself on a curved, polished wooden bench,

3690
04:48:35,920 --> 04:48:38,160
where he could watch cars approaching the airport.

3691
04:48:38,880 --> 04:48:42,400
Anyhow, he said to himself, I'm here in time to join the rest of the group.

3692
04:48:42,400 --> 04:48:44,880
They haven't left town yet, and that's what matters.

3693
04:48:45,840 --> 04:48:47,600
The elderly official called.

3694
04:48:47,600 --> 04:48:49,360
Mr.—come over here, sec.

3695
04:48:50,160 --> 04:48:52,160
Getting up, Joe crossed the waiting room.

3696
04:48:52,160 --> 04:48:52,640
What's wrong?

3697
04:48:53,520 --> 04:48:55,360
This nickel you gave me.

3698
04:48:55,920 --> 04:48:58,160
The official had been scrutinizing it all this time.

3699
04:48:59,600 --> 04:49:01,840
It's a buffalo nickel, Joe said.

3700
04:49:01,840 --> 04:49:03,520
Isn't that the right coin for this period?

3701
04:49:04,240 --> 04:49:07,200
This nickel is dated 1940.

3702
04:49:07,760 --> 04:49:10,400
The elderly official eyed him, unblinkingly.

3703
04:49:11,520 --> 04:49:15,840
With a groan, Joe got out his remaining coins, again sorted among them.

3704
04:49:15,840 --> 04:49:20,000
At last he found a 1938 nickel and tossed it down before the official.

3705
04:49:20,880 --> 04:49:22,720
Keep them both, he said.

3706
04:49:23,600 --> 04:49:26,640
And once more seated himself on the polished curved bench.

3707
04:49:27,520 --> 04:49:31,040
When he'd get counterfeit money every now and then, the official said.

3708
04:49:31,920 --> 04:49:32,800
Joe said nothing.

3709
04:49:33,280 --> 04:49:35,760
He turned his attention to the semi-high boy,

3710
04:49:35,760 --> 04:49:39,680
Odiolla Radio, playing by itself off in a corner of the waiting room.

3711
04:49:39,680 --> 04:49:42,880
The announcer was plugging a toothpaste called Ipana.

3712
04:49:43,680 --> 04:49:46,880
I wonder how long I'm going to have to wait here, Joe asked himself.

3713
04:49:46,880 --> 04:49:51,040
It made him nervous now that he had come so close physically to the inertials.

3714
04:49:51,040 --> 04:49:54,480
I'd hate to make it this far, he thought, within a few miles, and then—

3715
04:49:55,520 --> 04:49:58,480
He stopped his thoughts at that point, then simply sat.

3716
04:49:58,720 --> 04:50:05,840
Half an hour later, in 1930, Willis Knight, 87, putt-putted onto the airfield's parking lot,

3717
04:50:05,840 --> 04:50:10,640
a hempen, homespun individual wearing a conspicuously black suit,

3718
04:50:10,640 --> 04:50:15,040
emerged and shaded his eyes with the flat of his hand in order to see into the waiting room.

3719
04:50:15,840 --> 04:50:16,720
Joe approached him.

3720
04:50:17,360 --> 04:50:18,800
Are you Mr. Bliss, he asked?

3721
04:50:19,600 --> 04:50:20,320
Certainly I am.

3722
04:50:20,960 --> 04:50:26,080
Bliss briefly shook hands with him, meanwhile emitting a strong smell of sen-sen,

3723
04:50:26,080 --> 04:50:29,600
then got back at once into the Willis Knight and restarted the motor.

3724
04:50:29,600 --> 04:50:31,600
Come along, Mr. Chair, please hurry.

3725
04:50:31,600 --> 04:50:34,480
We may still be able to attend a part of the service.

3726
04:50:34,480 --> 04:50:39,600
Father Abernathy generally speaks quite a while on such important occasions as this.

3727
04:50:40,640 --> 04:50:43,200
Joe got into the front seat beside Mr. Bliss.

3728
04:50:43,200 --> 04:50:47,120
A moment later they clanked onto the road leading to downtown Des Moines,

3729
04:50:47,120 --> 04:50:51,120
rushing along at speeds sometimes reaching forty miles an hour.

3730
04:50:52,240 --> 04:50:54,480
You're an employee of Mr. Rancis, sir?

3731
04:50:54,480 --> 04:50:55,520
Bliss asked.

3732
04:50:55,520 --> 04:50:56,480
Right, Joe said.

3733
04:50:57,360 --> 04:51:03,360
Unusual line of business that Mr. Rancis was in, and I'm not quite sure I understand it.

3734
04:51:04,240 --> 04:51:08,080
Bliss honked at a red setter which adventured onto the asphalt pavement,

3735
04:51:08,080 --> 04:51:11,440
the dog retreated giving the Willis Knight its pompous right of way.

3736
04:51:12,080 --> 04:51:14,400
What does psionic mean?

3737
04:51:14,400 --> 04:51:17,280
Several of Mr. Rancis's employees have used the term.

3738
04:51:18,000 --> 04:51:20,400
Parapsychological powers, Joe said.

3739
04:51:20,960 --> 04:51:25,600
Mental force operating directly without any intervening physical agency.

3740
04:51:26,400 --> 04:51:28,240
Mystical powers, you mean?

3741
04:51:28,240 --> 04:51:29,680
Like knowing the future?

3742
04:51:30,400 --> 04:51:35,680
The reason I ask that is that several of you people have talked about the futures if it already exists.

3743
04:51:36,640 --> 04:51:37,520
Not to me.

3744
04:51:37,520 --> 04:51:42,800
They didn't say anything about it except to each other, but I overheard, you know, how it is.

3745
04:51:43,760 --> 04:51:46,480
Are you people mediums?

3746
04:51:46,480 --> 04:51:47,120
Is that it?

3747
04:51:48,080 --> 04:51:49,440
In a manner of speaking,

3748
04:51:50,000 --> 04:51:52,080
what do you foresee about the war in Europe?

3749
04:51:52,880 --> 04:51:59,200
Joe said Germany and Japan will lose, the United States will get into it on December 7, 1941.

3750
04:52:00,000 --> 04:52:03,360
He lapsed into silence then, not feeling inclined to discuss it.

3751
04:52:03,360 --> 04:52:06,320
He had his own problems to occupy his attention.

3752
04:52:07,280 --> 04:52:09,920
I must shriner myself, Bliss said.

3753
04:52:11,520 --> 04:52:14,320
What is the rest of the group experiencing, Joe wondered?

3754
04:52:14,960 --> 04:52:18,400
This reality, the United States of 1939?

3755
04:52:18,400 --> 04:52:23,520
Or when I rejoin them, will my regression be reversed, placing me at a later period?

3756
04:52:23,520 --> 04:52:24,320
Good question.

3757
04:52:25,120 --> 04:52:30,800
Because collectively they would have to find their way back 53 years to the reasonable and

3758
04:52:30,800 --> 04:52:34,720
proper form constituents of contemporary unregressed time.

3759
04:52:35,600 --> 04:52:39,760
If the group as a whole had experienced the same amount of regression as he had,

3760
04:52:40,560 --> 04:52:44,720
then his joining them would not help him or them, except in one regard.

3761
04:52:44,720 --> 04:52:48,000
He might be spared the ordeal of undergoing further world decay.

3762
04:52:48,880 --> 04:52:53,120
On the other hand, this reality of 1939 seemed fairly stable.

3763
04:52:53,120 --> 04:52:56,400
In the last 24 hours it had managed to remain virtually constant.

3764
04:52:57,120 --> 04:53:00,640
But he reflected that might be due to my drawing nearer to the group.

3765
04:53:01,760 --> 04:53:06,320
On the other hand, the 1939 jar of ubiquid liver and kidney bomb had reverted back an

3766
04:53:06,320 --> 04:53:13,520
additional 80 odd years from a spray can to jar to wooden mold bottle within a few hours.

3767
04:53:14,480 --> 04:53:19,520
Like the 1908 cage elevator which Al alone had seen, but that wasn't so.

3768
04:53:20,320 --> 04:53:24,640
The short fat pilot, Sandy Gispersen, had also seen the wooden mold bottle,

3769
04:53:24,640 --> 04:53:27,440
the elixir of ubiqu as it had become finally.

3770
04:53:28,240 --> 04:53:30,640
This was not a private vision.

3771
04:53:30,640 --> 04:53:33,440
It had, in fact, gotten him here to Des Moines.

3772
04:53:34,240 --> 04:53:37,760
And the pilot had seen the reversion of the Lissal as well.

3773
04:53:38,960 --> 04:53:42,560
Something entirely different had overtaken Al, it would seem.

3774
04:53:42,640 --> 04:53:44,800
At least he hoped so, prayed so.

3775
04:53:46,160 --> 04:53:49,200
Suppose he reflected we can't reverse our regression.

3776
04:53:49,200 --> 04:53:53,040
Suppose we remain here, the balance of our lives.

3777
04:53:55,040 --> 04:53:56,000
Is that so bad?

3778
04:53:56,560 --> 04:54:00,960
We can get used to nine-tube screen-grid high-boy Philco radios,

3779
04:54:01,600 --> 04:54:06,240
although they won't really be necessary in as much as the super-hetrodine circuit has

3780
04:54:06,240 --> 04:54:09,920
already been invented, although I haven't as yet run across one.

3781
04:54:10,640 --> 04:54:14,720
We could learn to drive American Austin motor-cars selling for $445.

3782
04:54:16,080 --> 04:54:21,040
A sum that had popped into his mind seemingly at random, but which he intuited was correct.

3783
04:54:21,840 --> 04:54:25,680
Once we get jobs and earn money of this period, he said to himself,

3784
04:54:26,240 --> 04:54:29,760
we won't be traveling aboard antique Curtis Wright bi-planes.

3785
04:54:30,400 --> 04:54:35,920
After all, four years ago, in 1935, Trans-Pacific Service by four engine China Clippers was

3786
04:54:35,920 --> 04:54:42,960
inaugurated. The Ford Trimotor is an 11-year-old plane by now. To these people it's a relic,

3787
04:54:42,960 --> 04:54:47,040
and the bi-plane I came here on is, even to them, a museum piece.

3788
04:54:48,080 --> 04:54:53,120
That LaSalle I had before it reverted was a considerable piece of machinery. I felt

3789
04:54:53,120 --> 04:54:54,800
real satisfaction driving it.

3790
04:54:55,600 --> 04:55:02,480
What about Russia, Mr. Bliss was asking, in the war? I mean, do we wipe out those reds?

3791
04:55:02,480 --> 04:55:03,680
Can you see that far ahead?

3792
04:55:04,640 --> 04:55:08,640
Joe said, Russia will fight on the same side as the USA.

3793
04:55:09,440 --> 04:55:13,760
And all the other objects and entities and artifacts of this world, he mulled.

3794
04:55:14,560 --> 04:55:21,040
Medicine will be a major drawback. Let's see. Just about now they should be using the Sulfur drugs.

3795
04:55:21,040 --> 04:55:23,200
Well, it's going to be serious for us when we become ill.

3796
04:55:23,920 --> 04:55:27,200
And dental work isn't going to be much fun either.

3797
04:55:27,200 --> 04:55:29,760
They're still working with hot drills and novocaine.

3798
04:55:30,560 --> 04:55:35,040
Fluoride toothpaste's haven't even come into being. That's another 20 years in the future.

3799
04:55:35,680 --> 04:55:41,280
On our side, Bliss sputtered, that communists? That's impossible. They've got that packed with the

3800
04:55:41,280 --> 04:55:48,160
Nazis. Germany will violate that pack, Joe said. Hitler will attack the Soviet Union in June 1941.

3801
04:55:48,160 --> 04:55:49,600
And wipe it out, I hope.

3802
04:55:50,400 --> 04:55:54,720
Startled out of his preoccupations, Joe turned to look closely at Mr. Bliss,

3803
04:55:54,720 --> 04:55:58,480
driving his nine-year-old Willis Knight. Bliss said,

3804
04:55:58,480 --> 04:56:01,520
those communists are the real menace, not the Germans.

3805
04:56:02,080 --> 04:56:07,680
Take the treatment of the Jews. You know who makes a lot out of that Jews in this country.

3806
04:56:07,680 --> 04:56:12,080
A lot of them not citizens, but refugees, living on public welfare.

3807
04:56:12,640 --> 04:56:16,880
I think the Nazis certainly have been a little extreme in some of the things they've done to

3808
04:56:16,880 --> 04:56:24,400
the Jews. But basically, there's been the Jewish question for a long time. And something, although

3809
04:56:24,400 --> 04:56:31,120
maybe not so vile as those concentration camps, had to be done about it. We have a similar problem

3810
04:56:31,120 --> 04:56:35,440
here in the United States, both with Jews and with the niggers. Eventually we're going to have to do

3811
04:56:35,440 --> 04:56:43,200
something about both. I never actually heard the term nigger used, Joe said, and found himself

3812
04:56:43,200 --> 04:56:49,440
appraising this era a little differently all at once. I forgot about this, he realized.

3813
04:56:50,400 --> 04:56:55,360
Lenberg is the one who's right about Germany, Bliss said. Have you ever listened to him speak?

3814
04:56:55,360 --> 04:56:58,560
I don't mean what the newspapers write it up like, but actually,

3815
04:56:59,200 --> 04:57:02,880
he slowed the car to a stop for a semaphore-style stop signal.

3816
04:57:03,600 --> 04:57:08,480
Take Senator Bora and Senator Nye. If it wasn't for them, Roosevelt would be selling

3817
04:57:08,480 --> 04:57:15,680
munitions to England and getting us into a war that's not our war. Roosevelt is so darn interested

3818
04:57:15,680 --> 04:57:20,400
in repealing the arms embargo clause of the neutrality bill, he wants us to get into the war.

3819
04:57:21,040 --> 04:57:25,440
American people aren't going to support him. American people aren't interested in fighting

3820
04:57:25,440 --> 04:57:31,840
England's war or anybody else's war. The signal clanged and a green semaphore swung out.

3821
04:57:32,400 --> 04:57:36,320
Bliss shifted into low gear and the Willis Knight bumbled forward,

3822
04:57:36,320 --> 04:57:39,360
melding with downtown Des Moines midday traffic.

3823
04:57:40,160 --> 04:57:43,440
You're not going to enjoy the next five years, Joe said.

3824
04:57:43,440 --> 04:57:46,960
Why not? The whole state of Iowa is behind me in what I believe.

3825
04:57:47,680 --> 04:57:52,160
You know what I think about you employees at Mr. Runceter? From what you've said and from what

3826
04:57:52,160 --> 04:57:58,480
those others said what I overheard? I think you're professional agitators, Bliss glanced at Joe with

3827
04:57:58,480 --> 04:58:05,440
uncowed bravado. Joe said nothing. He watched the old-time brick and wood and concrete buildings

3828
04:58:05,520 --> 04:58:10,960
go by, the quaint cars, most of which appeared to be black, and wondered if he was the only one

3829
04:58:10,960 --> 04:58:16,160
of the group who had been confronted by this particular aspect of the world of 1939.

3830
04:58:17,360 --> 04:58:22,800
In New York, he told himself it'll be different. This is the Bible Belt, the isolationist Middle

3831
04:58:22,800 --> 04:58:29,280
West. We won't be living here. We'll be on either the East Coast or the West. But instinctively,

3832
04:58:29,280 --> 04:58:33,760
he sensed that a major problem for all of them had exposed itself just now.

3833
04:58:34,560 --> 04:58:41,760
We know too much, he realized, to live comfortably in this time segment. If we had regressed 20 years

3834
04:58:41,760 --> 04:58:48,160
or 30 years, we could probably make the psychological transition. It might not be interesting to once

3835
04:58:48,160 --> 04:58:52,960
more live through the Gemini spacewalks and the creaking first Apollo flights, but at least it

3836
04:58:52,960 --> 04:59:00,400
would be possible. But at this point in time, they're still listening to 10-inch 78 records of

3837
04:59:00,400 --> 04:59:09,280
two black crows and Joe Penner and Mert and Marge. The depression is still going on. In our time,

3838
04:59:09,280 --> 04:59:14,640
we maintain colonies on Mars, on Luna. We're perfecting workable interstellar flight.

3839
04:59:15,440 --> 04:59:21,040
These people have not been able to cope with the dust bowl of Oklahoma. This is a world that lives

3840
04:59:21,040 --> 04:59:26,800
in terms of William Jennings Bryan's oratory. The Scopes Monkey Trial is a vivid reality here.

3841
04:59:27,440 --> 04:59:33,440
He thought, there is no way we can adapt to their viewpoint, their moral, political, sociological

3842
04:59:33,440 --> 04:59:39,760
environment. To them, we're professional agitators, more alien than the Nazis, probably even more

3843
04:59:39,760 --> 04:59:44,240
of a menace than the Communist Party. We're the most dangerous agitators that this time

3844
04:59:44,240 --> 04:59:48,080
segment has yet had to deal with. Bliss is absolutely right.

3845
04:59:49,040 --> 04:59:52,080
Where are you people from? Bliss was asking.

3846
04:59:52,080 --> 04:59:54,400
Not from any part of the United States. Am I correct?

3847
04:59:55,200 --> 04:59:59,040
Joe said, you're correct. We're from the North American Confederation.

3848
05:00:00,080 --> 05:00:03,360
From his pocket, he brought forth a rancidur quarter which he handed to Bliss.

3849
05:00:03,920 --> 05:00:09,360
Be my guest, he said. Glancing at the coin, Bliss gulped and quavered,

3850
05:00:09,360 --> 05:00:15,680
the profile on this coin. This is the deceased. This is Mr. Rancidur. He took another look and

3851
05:00:15,680 --> 05:00:19,600
blanched. And the date? 1990.

3852
05:00:20,640 --> 05:00:23,280
Don't spend it all in one place, Joe said.

3853
05:00:24,800 --> 05:00:28,720
When the Willis Knight reached the simple shepherd mortuary, the surface had already

3854
05:00:28,720 --> 05:00:33,600
ended. On the wide, white, wooden steps of the two-story frame building, a group of people

3855
05:00:33,600 --> 05:00:40,640
stood and Joe recognized all of them. There, at last, they were. Edidorn, Tippi Jackson,

3856
05:00:40,640 --> 05:00:48,080
John Ild, Francie Spanish, Tito Apostos, Don Denny, Sammy Mundo, Fred Zafsky, and Pat.

3857
05:00:49,200 --> 05:00:54,400
My wife, he said to himself, impressed once again by the sight of her, the dramatic dark hair,

3858
05:00:54,400 --> 05:01:00,880
the intense coloring of her eyes and skin, all the powerful contrasts radiating from her.

3859
05:01:02,000 --> 05:01:07,040
No, he said aloud as he stepped from the parked car. She's not my wife. She wiped that out.

3860
05:01:07,840 --> 05:01:14,000
But he remembered she kept the ring, the unique rot-silver and jade wedding ring which she and I

3861
05:01:14,000 --> 05:01:20,320
picked out. That's all that remains. But what a shock to see her again, to regain for an instant

3862
05:01:20,320 --> 05:01:26,640
the ghostly shroud of a marriage that has been abolished, that had in fact never existed,

3863
05:01:26,640 --> 05:01:31,360
except for this ring. And whenever she felt like it, she could obliterate the ring, too.

3864
05:01:32,320 --> 05:01:38,800
Hi, Joe Chip, she said, in her cool, almost mocking voice, her intense eyes fixed on him,

3865
05:01:38,800 --> 05:01:45,440
appraising him. Hello, he said awkwardly. The others greeted him, too, but that did not seem

3866
05:01:45,440 --> 05:01:48,320
so important. Pat had snared his attention.

3867
05:01:49,280 --> 05:01:55,680
No, Al Hammond, Don Denny asked. Joe said, Al's dead. Wendy Wright is dead.

3868
05:01:56,400 --> 05:02:00,080
We know about Wendy, Pat said calmly.

3869
05:02:00,080 --> 05:02:06,080
No, we didn't know, Don Denny said. We assumed, but we weren't sure. I wasn't sure.

3870
05:02:06,720 --> 05:02:09,840
To Joe, he said, what happened to them? What killed them?

3871
05:02:10,720 --> 05:02:12,480
They wore out, Joe said.

3872
05:02:13,200 --> 05:02:17,760
Why? Tito Apostos said, hoarsely crowding into the circle of people surrounding Joe.

3873
05:02:18,400 --> 05:02:24,080
Pat Conley said, Last thing you said to us, Joe Chip, back in New York before you went off with

3874
05:02:24,080 --> 05:02:31,200
Hammond. I know what I said, Joe said. Pat continued, You said something about years. It had been

3875
05:02:31,200 --> 05:02:34,960
too long, you said. What does that mean? Something about time.

3876
05:02:36,080 --> 05:02:42,960
Mr. Chip, Edidorn said agitatedly, Since we came here to this place, this town has radically changed.

3877
05:02:42,960 --> 05:02:46,080
None of us understand it. Do you see what we see?

3878
05:02:46,080 --> 05:02:50,560
With her hand she indicated the mortuary building, then the street and the other buildings.

3879
05:02:51,520 --> 05:02:54,240
I'm not sure, Joe said, What it is you see.

3880
05:02:55,040 --> 05:03:00,160
Come on, ship, Tito Apostos said with anger, Don't mess around. Simply tell us for Christ's sake,

3881
05:03:00,160 --> 05:03:04,400
What this place looks like to you. That vehicle, he gestured toward the Willis Knight.

3882
05:03:04,400 --> 05:03:07,680
You arrived in that. Tell us what it is. Tell us what you arrived in.

3883
05:03:08,480 --> 05:03:11,360
They all waited, all of them, Intently watching, Joe.

3884
05:03:12,560 --> 05:03:19,360
Mr. Chip, Sammy Mundo stammered, That's a real old automobile. That's what it is, right?

3885
05:03:19,360 --> 05:03:22,240
He giggled. How old is it, exactly?

3886
05:03:23,280 --> 05:03:26,880
After pause, Joe said, 62 years old.

3887
05:03:27,600 --> 05:03:31,920
That will make you 1930, tippy Jackson said to Don Denny,

3888
05:03:31,920 --> 05:03:33,760
Which is pretty close to what we figured.

3889
05:03:34,640 --> 05:03:39,600
We figured 1939, Don Denny said to Joe in a level voice,

3890
05:03:39,600 --> 05:03:45,760
A moderate, detached, mature baritone voice, Without undue emotionality,

3891
05:03:45,760 --> 05:03:47,280
Even under these circumstances,

3892
05:03:49,360 --> 05:03:52,160
Joe said, It's fairly easy to establish that.

3893
05:03:52,160 --> 05:03:56,720
I took a look at a newspaper at my con app back in New York, September 12th.

3894
05:03:56,720 --> 05:04:00,400
So today is September 13, 1939.

3895
05:04:01,120 --> 05:04:03,680
The French think they've reached the Siegfried line,

3896
05:04:04,320 --> 05:04:07,680
Which in itself, John Hilt said, Is a million laughs.

3897
05:04:08,720 --> 05:04:13,920
I hoped, Joe said, That you as a group were experiencing a later reality.

3898
05:04:13,920 --> 05:04:16,880
Well, so it goes.

3899
05:04:16,880 --> 05:04:23,200
If it's 1939, it's 1939, Fred Zafke said in a squeaky high-pitched voice.

3900
05:04:23,200 --> 05:04:25,920
Naturally, we all experience it. What else can we do?

3901
05:04:25,920 --> 05:04:28,240
He flacked his long arms energetically,

3902
05:04:28,240 --> 05:04:30,080
Appealing to the others for their agreement.

3903
05:04:30,880 --> 05:04:34,160
Flirt go off, Zafke, Tito Apostos said with annoyance.

3904
05:04:34,960 --> 05:04:37,680
To Pat, Joe Chip said, What do you say about this?

3905
05:04:38,480 --> 05:04:39,360
She shrugged.

3906
05:04:39,360 --> 05:04:41,280
Don't shrug, he said, Answer.

3907
05:04:42,160 --> 05:04:44,400
We've gone back in time, Pat said.

3908
05:04:44,960 --> 05:04:46,080
Not really, Joe said.

3909
05:04:46,880 --> 05:04:48,800
Then what have we done, Pat said?

3910
05:04:48,800 --> 05:04:50,400
Gone forward in time, is that it?

3911
05:04:51,280 --> 05:04:52,880
Joe said, We haven't gone anywhere.

3912
05:04:52,880 --> 05:04:54,480
We're where we've always been.

3913
05:04:54,480 --> 05:04:58,080
But for some reason, for one of several possible reasons,

3914
05:04:58,080 --> 05:05:00,160
Reality has receded.

3915
05:05:00,160 --> 05:05:03,680
It's lost its underlying support and its ebb back to previous forms.

3916
05:05:03,680 --> 05:05:07,360
Forms it took 53 years ago. It may regress further.

3917
05:05:08,240 --> 05:05:10,800
I'm more interested at this point in knowing if Runceter has

3918
05:05:10,880 --> 05:05:12,160
manifested himself to you.

3919
05:05:13,040 --> 05:05:16,720
Runceter, Don Denny said this time with undue emotionality,

3920
05:05:16,720 --> 05:05:20,000
is lying inside this building in his casket dead as a herring.

3921
05:05:20,000 --> 05:05:22,320
That's the only manifestation we've had of him.

3922
05:05:22,320 --> 05:05:23,680
And that's the only one we're going to get.

3923
05:05:24,560 --> 05:05:28,240
Does the word Yubic mean anything to you, Mr. Chip?

3924
05:05:28,240 --> 05:05:29,520
Francesca Spanish said.

3925
05:05:30,720 --> 05:05:33,200
It took him a moment to absorb what she had said.

3926
05:05:34,400 --> 05:05:36,320
Jesus Christ, he said then.

3927
05:05:36,320 --> 05:05:40,160
Can't you distinguish manifestations of fancy has dreams?

3928
05:05:40,160 --> 05:05:42,960
Tippie Jackson said. She's always had them.

3929
05:05:42,960 --> 05:05:44,880
Tell me a Yubic dream, Francie.

3930
05:05:45,520 --> 05:05:48,880
To Joe, she said, Francie will not tell you her Yubic dream

3931
05:05:48,880 --> 05:05:50,640
as she calls it. She had it last night.

3932
05:05:51,680 --> 05:05:53,920
I could eat that because that's what it is.

3933
05:05:53,920 --> 05:05:56,000
Francesca Spanish said fiercely.

3934
05:05:56,000 --> 05:05:59,840
She clasped her hands together in a spasm of excited agitation.

3935
05:05:59,840 --> 05:06:04,240
Listen, Mr. Chip, it wasn't like any dream I've ever had before.

3936
05:06:04,240 --> 05:06:09,520
A great hand came down from the sky like the arm and hand of God.

3937
05:06:09,520 --> 05:06:12,400
Enormous the size of a mountain.

3938
05:06:12,400 --> 05:06:15,200
And I knew at the time how important it was.

3939
05:06:15,200 --> 05:06:19,440
The hand was closed, made into a rock like fist.

3940
05:06:19,440 --> 05:06:21,760
And I knew it contained something of value.

3941
05:06:21,760 --> 05:06:26,320
So great that my life and the lives of everyone else on earth

3942
05:06:26,320 --> 05:06:27,520
depended on it.

3943
05:06:27,520 --> 05:06:29,680
And I waited for the fist to open.

3944
05:06:29,680 --> 05:06:31,600
And it did open.

3945
05:06:31,600 --> 05:06:34,000
And I saw what it contained.

3946
05:06:34,640 --> 05:06:36,560
An aerosol spray can.

3947
05:06:36,640 --> 05:06:38,000
Don Denny said dryly.

3948
05:06:38,560 --> 05:06:41,520
On the spray can, Francesca Spanish continued,

3949
05:06:41,520 --> 05:06:45,600
there was one word, great golden letters, glittering,

3950
05:06:45,600 --> 05:06:50,080
golden fire, spelling out Yubic, nothing else.

3951
05:06:50,080 --> 05:06:51,680
Just that strange word.

3952
05:06:52,720 --> 05:06:56,320
And then the hand closed up again around the spray can

3953
05:06:56,320 --> 05:06:58,480
and the hand and arm disappeared,

3954
05:06:58,480 --> 05:07:01,520
drawn back up into a sort of gray overcast.

3955
05:07:02,400 --> 05:07:05,200
Today, before the funeral services, I looked in the dictionary

3956
05:07:05,200 --> 05:07:08,800
and I called the public library, but no one knew that word.

3957
05:07:08,800 --> 05:07:10,640
Or even what language it is.

3958
05:07:10,640 --> 05:07:12,080
And it isn't in the dictionary.

3959
05:07:12,080 --> 05:07:14,480
It isn't English, the librarian told me.

3960
05:07:14,480 --> 05:07:16,720
There's a Latin word very close to it.

3961
05:07:17,280 --> 05:07:18,400
Ubiquay.

3962
05:07:18,400 --> 05:07:20,720
It means everywhere, Joe said.

3963
05:07:21,680 --> 05:07:23,440
Francesca Spanish nodded.

3964
05:07:23,440 --> 05:07:24,800
That's what it means.

3965
05:07:24,800 --> 05:07:26,080
But no Yubic.

3966
05:07:26,080 --> 05:07:28,000
And that's how it was spelled in the dream.

3967
05:07:28,800 --> 05:07:31,200
They're the same word, Joe said, just different spellings.

3968
05:07:31,920 --> 05:07:33,200
How do you know that?

3969
05:07:33,200 --> 05:07:35,040
Pat Conley said, archly.

3970
05:07:35,840 --> 05:07:38,880
Ronseter appeared to me yesterday, Joe said,

3971
05:07:38,880 --> 05:07:41,520
in a tape-TV commercial that he made before his death.

3972
05:07:42,320 --> 05:07:43,600
He did not elaborate.

3973
05:07:43,600 --> 05:07:47,280
It seemed too complex to explain, at least at this particular time.

3974
05:07:48,240 --> 05:07:51,360
You miserable fool, Pat Conley said to him.

3975
05:07:52,080 --> 05:07:55,840
Why, he asked, is that your idea of a manifestation of a dead man?

3976
05:07:56,480 --> 05:07:59,120
You might as well consider letters he wrote before his death

3977
05:07:59,120 --> 05:08:05,360
manifestations, or interoffice memos that he transcribed over the years, or even—

3978
05:08:06,160 --> 05:08:09,360
Joe said, I'm going inside and take a last look at Ronseter.

3979
05:08:10,000 --> 05:08:14,320
He departed from the group, leaving them standing there, and made his way up the wide

3980
05:08:14,320 --> 05:08:18,640
board steps and into the dark, cool interior of the mortuary.

3981
05:08:20,560 --> 05:08:21,200
Emptiness.

3982
05:08:22,320 --> 05:08:27,840
He saw no one, only a large chamber with pew-like rows of seats, and at the far end

3983
05:08:27,920 --> 05:08:29,840
a casket surrounded by flowers.

3984
05:08:30,640 --> 05:08:35,680
Off in a small side room, an old-fashioned reed-pump organ, and a few wooden folding chairs.

3985
05:08:36,240 --> 05:08:41,920
The mortuary smelled of dust and flowers, a sweet stale mixture that repelled him.

3986
05:08:42,880 --> 05:08:48,240
Think of all the Iowans he thought who've embraced eternity in this listless room.

3987
05:08:48,880 --> 05:08:52,480
Varnished floors, handkerchiefs, heavy, dark wool suits,

3988
05:08:53,040 --> 05:08:59,200
everything but pennies placed over the dead eyes, and the organ playing symmetric little hymns.

3989
05:09:00,560 --> 05:09:03,440
He reached the casket, hesitated, then looked down.

3990
05:09:04,800 --> 05:09:11,520
A singed, dehydrated heap of bones lay at one end of the casket, culminating in a paper-like

3991
05:09:11,520 --> 05:09:16,560
skull that leered up at him. The eyes recessed like dried grapes.

3992
05:09:17,280 --> 05:09:22,320
Tatters of cloth with bristle-like woven spines had collected near the tiny body,

3993
05:09:22,320 --> 05:09:28,320
as if blown there by wind, as if the body breathing had cluttered itself with them by its

3994
05:09:28,320 --> 05:09:35,760
wheezing meager processes, inhalation and exhalation, which had now ceased. Nothing stirred.

3995
05:09:36,640 --> 05:09:42,480
The mysterious change which had also degraded Wendy Wright and Al had reached its end.

3996
05:09:43,040 --> 05:09:47,280
Evidently a long time ago, years ago, he thought remembering Wendy.

3997
05:09:48,240 --> 05:09:52,320
Had the others in the group seen this, or had it happened since the services?

3998
05:09:53,600 --> 05:09:59,200
Joe reached out, took hold of the oak lid of the casket, and shut it. The thump of wood

3999
05:09:59,200 --> 05:10:03,760
against wood echoed throughout the empty mortuary, but no one heard it, no one appeared.

4000
05:10:04,960 --> 05:10:09,760
Blinded by tears of fright, he made his way back out of the dust-stricken silent room,

4001
05:10:09,760 --> 05:10:12,240
back into the weak sunlight of late afternoon.

4002
05:10:13,120 --> 05:10:16,960
What's the matter, Don Denney asked him as he rejoined the group?

4003
05:10:16,960 --> 05:10:18,720
Joe said, Nothing.

4004
05:10:19,840 --> 05:10:23,840
You look scared out of your goony wits, Pat Connolly said acutely.

4005
05:10:23,840 --> 05:10:28,080
Nothing! He stared at her with deep infuriated hostility.

4006
05:10:28,880 --> 05:10:33,760
Tippi Jackson said to him, While you were in there, did you by any chance happen to see Edie

4007
05:10:33,760 --> 05:10:38,000
Dorn? She's missing, John Ilde said by way of explanation.

4008
05:10:38,800 --> 05:10:44,480
But she was just out here, Joe protested. All day she's been saying she felt terribly cold and

4009
05:10:44,480 --> 05:10:49,760
tired. Don Denney said, It may be that she went back to the hotel. She said something about it

4010
05:10:49,760 --> 05:10:55,200
earlier, that she wanted to lie down and take a nap right after the services. She's probably all right.

4011
05:10:56,000 --> 05:11:02,720
Joe said, She's probably dead. To all of them, he said, I thought you understood.

4012
05:11:03,440 --> 05:11:08,640
If any one of us gets separated from the group he won't survive, what happened to Wendy and Al

4013
05:11:09,200 --> 05:11:15,040
and Runceter? He broke off. Runceter was killed in the blast, Don Denney said.

4014
05:11:16,000 --> 05:11:22,320
We were all killed in the blast, Joe said. I know that because Runceter told me. He

4015
05:11:22,320 --> 05:11:26,800
wrote it on the wall of the men's room back at our New York offices, and I saw it again on

4016
05:11:26,880 --> 05:11:30,960
what you're saying is insane. Pat Connolly said sharply, interrupting him.

4017
05:11:31,520 --> 05:11:36,080
Is Runceter dead or isn't he? Are we dead or aren't we? First you say one thing,

4018
05:11:36,080 --> 05:11:41,520
then you say another. Can't you be consistent? Try to be consistent, John Ilde put in. The others,

4019
05:11:41,520 --> 05:11:47,600
their faces pinched and creased with worry, nodded in mute agreement. Joe said, I can tell you what

4020
05:11:47,600 --> 05:11:52,240
the graffiti said. I can tell you about the worn out tape recorder, the instructions that came with

4021
05:11:52,720 --> 05:11:57,280
it. I can tell you about Runceter's TV commercial, the note in the carton of cigarettes in Baltimore.

4022
05:11:57,280 --> 05:12:02,160
I can tell you about the label on the flask of elixir of Ubik, but I can't make it all add up.

4023
05:12:03,760 --> 05:12:08,320
In any case, we have to get to your hotel to try to reach Edidorn before she withers away and

4024
05:12:08,320 --> 05:12:14,000
invariably expires. Where can we get a taxi? The Marjory has provided us with a car to use while

4025
05:12:14,000 --> 05:12:19,360
we're here, Don Denney said. That pierced arrow sitting over there, he pointed. They hurried

4026
05:12:19,360 --> 05:12:24,880
toward it. We're not all of us going to be able to fit in, Tippi Jackson said,

4027
05:12:24,880 --> 05:12:28,640
as Don Denney tugged the solid iron door open and got inside.

4028
05:12:29,520 --> 05:12:34,000
Ask Bliss if we can take the Willis Knight, Joe said. He started up the engine of the pierce

4029
05:12:34,000 --> 05:12:38,880
arrow, and as soon as everyone possible had gotten into the car drove out onto the busy

4030
05:12:38,880 --> 05:12:44,320
main street of Des Moines. The Willis Knight followed close behind its horn honking dolefully

4031
05:12:44,320 --> 05:12:45,680
to tell Joe it was there.

4032
05:12:46,640 --> 05:12:49,440
12

4033
05:12:51,520 --> 05:12:57,360
Pop tasty Ubik into your toaster, made only from fresh fruit and healthful all-vegetable

4034
05:12:57,360 --> 05:13:04,320
shortening. Ubik makes breakfast of feast, put zing into your thing, safe when handled as directed.

4035
05:13:06,720 --> 05:13:11,040
One by one, Joe Chip said to himself as he piloted the big car through traffic,

4036
05:13:11,040 --> 05:13:17,600
we're succumbing. Something is wrong with my theory. Edie, by being with the group,

4037
05:13:17,600 --> 05:13:24,720
should have been immune. And I—it should have been me, he thought, sometime during my slow

4038
05:13:24,720 --> 05:13:30,640
flight from New York. What we'll have to do, he said to Don Denney, is make sure that anyone who

4039
05:13:30,640 --> 05:13:36,880
feels tired—that seems to be the first warning—tells the rest of us, and isn't allowed to wander away.

4040
05:13:37,840 --> 05:13:40,240
Twisting round to face those in the back seat, Don said,

4041
05:13:40,800 --> 05:13:44,640
do you all hear that? As soon as any of you feels tired, even a little bit,

4042
05:13:44,640 --> 05:13:48,640
report it to either Mr. Chip or myself. He turned back toward Joe.

4043
05:13:49,200 --> 05:13:50,320
And then what, he asked.

4044
05:13:51,040 --> 05:13:56,720
And then what, Joe? Pat Connolly echoed. What do we do then? Tell us how we do it, Joe, we're listening.

4045
05:13:57,760 --> 05:14:03,200
Joe said to her, it seems strange to me that your talent isn't coming into play.

4046
05:14:03,920 --> 05:14:08,320
This situation appears to me to be made for it. Why can't you go back fifteen minutes and

4047
05:14:08,320 --> 05:14:13,360
compel Edie Dorn not to wander off? Do what you did when I first introduced you to Runceter.

4048
05:14:14,480 --> 05:14:17,680
Gigi Ashwood introduced me to Mr. Runceter, Pat said.

4049
05:14:18,480 --> 05:14:23,600
So, you're not going to do anything, Joe said. Sammy Mundo giggled and said,

4050
05:14:24,320 --> 05:14:30,320
they had a fight last night while we were eating dinner. Ms. Connolly and Ms. Dorn—Ms. Connolly

4051
05:14:30,320 --> 05:14:33,280
doesn't like her. That's why she won't help.

4052
05:14:33,840 --> 05:14:39,040
I like Edie, Pat said. Do you have any reason for not making use of your talent?

4053
05:14:39,040 --> 05:14:43,760
Don Denny asked her. Joe's right. It's very strange and difficult to understand,

4054
05:14:43,760 --> 05:14:46,800
at least for me. Why exactly you don't try to help?

4055
05:14:48,480 --> 05:14:56,160
After pause, Pat said, my talent doesn't work anymore. It hasn't since the bomb blast on Luna.

4056
05:14:56,800 --> 05:15:02,800
Why didn't you say so, Joe said? Pat said, I didn't feel like saying so, goddamn it.

4057
05:15:03,440 --> 05:15:08,720
Why should I volunteer information like that that I can't do anything? I keep trying,

4058
05:15:08,720 --> 05:15:13,840
and it keeps not working. Nothing happens. And it's never been that way before. I've had the

4059
05:15:13,840 --> 05:15:21,200
talent virtually my entire life. When did—? Joe began. With Runceter, Pat said, on Luna,

4060
05:15:21,200 --> 05:15:22,640
right away, before you asked me.

4061
05:15:23,760 --> 05:15:29,360
So you knew that long ago, Joe said. I tried again in New York after you showed up from Zurich,

4062
05:15:29,360 --> 05:15:33,440
and it was obvious that something awful had happened to Wendy, and I've been trying now.

4063
05:15:33,440 --> 05:15:38,480
I started as soon as you said Edie was probably dead. Maybe it's because we're back in this

4064
05:15:38,480 --> 05:15:45,360
archaic time period. Maybe psionic talents don't work in 1939. But that wouldn't explain Luna.

4065
05:15:46,160 --> 05:15:50,080
Unless we had already traveled back here and we didn't realize it.

4066
05:15:51,200 --> 05:15:57,200
She lapsed into brooding, introverted silence. Dolly, she gazed out at the streets of Des Moines,

4067
05:15:57,200 --> 05:16:00,080
the bitter expression on her potent, wild face.

4068
05:16:01,120 --> 05:16:07,200
It fits in, Joe said to himself. Of course, her time-traveling talent no longer functions.

4069
05:16:07,200 --> 05:16:15,200
This is not really 1939, and we are outside of time entirely. This proves that Al was right,

4070
05:16:15,200 --> 05:16:20,640
the graffiti was right. This is half-life, as the couplets told us.

4071
05:16:22,000 --> 05:16:25,200
He did not, however, say this to the others with him in the car.

4072
05:16:25,200 --> 05:16:29,840
Why tell them it's hopeless, he said to himself. They're gonna find it out soon enough.

4073
05:16:30,480 --> 05:16:34,640
The smarter ones, such as Denny, probably understand it already,

4074
05:16:34,640 --> 05:16:38,000
based on what I've said and what they themselves have gone through.

4075
05:16:39,600 --> 05:16:43,760
This really bothers you, Don Denny said to him, that our talent no longer works.

4076
05:16:44,480 --> 05:16:48,320
Sure, he nodded. I hoped it might change the situation.

4077
05:16:49,120 --> 05:16:56,400
There's more, Denny said with acute intuition. I can tell by your—he gestured—tone of voice,

4078
05:16:56,400 --> 05:17:01,360
maybe. Anyhow, I know. This means something. It's important. It tells you something.

4079
05:17:02,400 --> 05:17:07,360
Do I keep going straight here, Joe said, slowing the pierce arrow at an intersection?

4080
05:17:07,840 --> 05:17:14,160
Turn right, Tippi Jackson said. Pat said, you'll see a brick building with a neon sign going up

4081
05:17:14,160 --> 05:17:21,680
and down the Maramonte Hotel, it's called, a terrible place. One bathroom for every two rooms,

4082
05:17:21,680 --> 05:17:28,480
and a tub instead of a shower, and the food—incredible. And the only drink they sell is something

4083
05:17:28,480 --> 05:17:34,720
called knee-high. I like the food, Don Denny said. Genuine cow meat, rather than protein

4084
05:17:34,800 --> 05:17:41,680
synthetics. Authentic salmon. Is your money good? Joe asked. And then he heard a high-pitched wine

4085
05:17:41,680 --> 05:17:45,840
echoing up and down the street behind him. What's that mean? he asked Denny.

4086
05:17:46,480 --> 05:17:53,680
I don't know, Denny said nervously. Sammy Mundo said, as a police siren. You didn't

4087
05:17:53,680 --> 05:17:58,960
give a signal before you turn. How could I, Joe said? There's no lever on the steering column.

4088
05:17:59,440 --> 05:18:05,440
You should have made a hand signal, Sammy said. The siren had become very close now. Joe turning

4089
05:18:05,440 --> 05:18:10,960
his head saw a motorcycle pulling up a breast with him. He slowed the car, uncertain as to what he

4090
05:18:10,960 --> 05:18:18,400
should do. Stop at the curb, Sammy advised him. Joe stopped the car at the curb. Stepping from

4091
05:18:18,400 --> 05:18:24,480
his motorcycle, the cop strolled up to Joe, a young rat-faced man with hard, large eyes.

4092
05:18:25,200 --> 05:18:28,960
He studied, Joe, and then said, Let me see your license, Mr.

4093
05:18:30,000 --> 05:18:35,520
I don't have one, Joe said. Make out the ticket and let us go. He could see the hotel now. To

4094
05:18:35,520 --> 05:18:41,200
Don Denny, he said, You better get over there, you and everyone else. The Willis night continued on

4095
05:18:41,200 --> 05:18:46,160
toward it. Don Denny, Pat, Sammy Mundo, and Tippi Jackson abandoned the car. They trotted

4096
05:18:46,160 --> 05:18:50,560
after the Willis night, which had begun to slow to a stop across from the hotel,

4097
05:18:50,560 --> 05:18:56,880
leaving Joe to face the cop alone. The cop said to Joe, Yemeni, on identification,

4098
05:18:57,520 --> 05:19:03,520
Joe handed him his wallet. With a purple indelible pencil, the cop rode out a ticket, tore it from

4099
05:19:03,520 --> 05:19:09,440
his pad, and passed it to Joe. Earlier the signal, no operator's license, the citation tells where

4100
05:19:09,440 --> 05:19:15,360
and when to appear. The cop slapped his ticket book shut, handed Joe his wallet, then sauntered back

4101
05:19:15,360 --> 05:19:20,880
to his motorcycle. He revved up his motor and then zoomed out into traffic without looking back.

4102
05:19:22,720 --> 05:19:28,160
For some obscure reason, Joe glanced over the citation before putting it away in his pocket

4103
05:19:29,120 --> 05:19:36,320
and read it once again slowly. In purple indelible pencil, the familiar scrolled handwriting said,

4104
05:19:37,200 --> 05:19:43,120
You are in much greater danger than I thought. What Pat Connolly said is,

4105
05:19:43,440 --> 05:19:49,520
There the message ceased in the middle of a sentence. He wondered how it would have continued.

4106
05:19:49,520 --> 05:19:54,880
Was there anything more on the citation? He turned it over, found nothing, returned again to the front

4107
05:19:54,880 --> 05:20:01,680
side. No further handwriting. But in squirrel agate type at the bottom of the slip of paper,

4108
05:20:01,680 --> 05:20:07,840
the following inscription, Try Archer's Drugstore for Reliable Household Remedies and Medicinal

4109
05:20:08,800 --> 05:20:12,880
Preparations of Tried and Tested Value, Economically Priced.

4110
05:20:14,000 --> 05:20:18,240
Not much to go on, Joe reflected, but still not what should have appeared at the bottom of

4111
05:20:18,240 --> 05:20:23,760
a demoing traffic citation. It was clearly another manifestation, as was the purple handwriting above

4112
05:20:23,760 --> 05:20:29,120
it. Getting out of the pier, Saron, he entered the nearest store of magazine, candy, and tobacco

4113
05:20:29,120 --> 05:20:34,160
supply shop. May I use your phone book? He asked the broad-beamed middle-aged proprietor.

4114
05:20:34,880 --> 05:20:38,560
In the rear, the proprietor said amably with a jerk of his heavy thumb.

4115
05:20:39,360 --> 05:20:44,000
Joe found the phone book, and in the dim recesses of the dark little store looked up Archer's

4116
05:20:44,000 --> 05:20:48,960
drugstore. He could not find it listed. Closing the phone book, he approached the proprietor,

4117
05:20:48,960 --> 05:20:53,040
who at the moment was engaged in selling a roll of necko wafers to a boy.

4118
05:20:53,920 --> 05:20:57,040
Do you know where I can find Archer's drugstore? Joe asked him.

4119
05:20:57,680 --> 05:21:03,680
Nowhere, the proprietor said. At least not any more? Why not? It's been close for years.

4120
05:21:04,320 --> 05:21:09,760
Joe said, tell me where it was. Anyhow, draw me a map.

4121
05:21:09,760 --> 05:21:14,080
Oh, you don't need a map. I can tell you where it was. The big man leaned forward, pointing

4122
05:21:14,080 --> 05:21:19,280
out the door of his shop. You see that barber pole there? Go over there, and then look north.

4123
05:21:19,840 --> 05:21:26,080
That's north, he indicated the direction. You'll see an old building with gables, yellow in color.

4124
05:21:26,080 --> 05:21:32,240
There's a couple of apartments over it still being used, but the store premises downstairs,

4125
05:21:32,240 --> 05:21:37,120
they're abandoned. You'll be able to make out the sign, though, Archer's drugstore, so you'll

4126
05:21:37,120 --> 05:21:43,360
know when you've found it. What happened is that Ed Archer came down with throat cancer and

4127
05:21:43,360 --> 05:21:48,800
thanks, Joe said, and started out of the store back into the pale mid-afternoon sunlight.

4128
05:21:48,800 --> 05:21:53,440
He walked rapidly across the street to the barber pole, and from that position looked new north.

4129
05:21:54,160 --> 05:21:58,400
He could see the tall, peeling yellow building at the periphery of his range of vision,

4130
05:21:59,200 --> 05:22:06,560
but something about it struck him as strange, a shimmer, an unsteadiness, as if the building

4131
05:22:06,560 --> 05:22:12,960
faded forward into stability and then retreated into insubstantial uncertainty. An oscillation,

4132
05:22:12,960 --> 05:22:19,360
each phase lasting a few seconds, and then blurring off into its opposite, a fairly regular

4133
05:22:19,360 --> 05:22:26,000
variability, as if an organic pulsation underlay the structure, as if he thought it's alive.

4134
05:22:26,080 --> 05:22:32,720
Maybe he thought I've come to the end. He began to walk toward the abandoned drugstore,

4135
05:22:32,720 --> 05:22:39,360
not taking his eyes from it. He watched it pulse. He watched it change between its two states,

4136
05:22:39,360 --> 05:22:43,920
and then as he got closer and closer to it, he discerned the nature of its alternate conditions.

4137
05:22:44,640 --> 05:22:50,640
At the amplitude of greater stability, it became a retail home art outlet of his own time period,

4138
05:22:50,640 --> 05:22:56,000
homeostatic in operation, a self-service enterprise selling 10,000 commodities for the

4139
05:22:56,000 --> 05:23:01,600
modern conapt. He had patronized such highly functional computer-controlled pseudo-merchants

4140
05:23:01,600 --> 05:23:08,880
throughout his adult life, and at the amplitude of insubstantiality, it resolved itself into a tiny

4141
05:23:08,880 --> 05:23:16,720
anachronistic drugstore with rococo ornamentation. In its meager window displays, he saw hernia

4142
05:23:16,720 --> 05:23:23,840
belts, rows of corrective eyeglasses, a mortar and pestle, jars of assorted tablets, a hand-printed

4143
05:23:23,840 --> 05:23:31,200
sign reading leeches, huge glass-stopper bottles that contained a Pandora's heritage of patent

4144
05:23:31,200 --> 05:23:37,680
medicines and placebo, and painted on a flat wood board running across the top of the windows,

4145
05:23:37,680 --> 05:23:46,000
the words, archers, drugstore. No sign, whatever, of an empty, abandoned, closed-up store.

4146
05:23:46,080 --> 05:23:55,520
Its 1939 stage had somehow been excluded. He thought, so, in entering it, I either revert

4147
05:23:55,520 --> 05:24:04,480
further, or I find myself back roughly in my own time. And it's the further reversion, the pre-1939

4148
05:24:04,480 --> 05:24:11,040
phase that I evidently need. Presently he stood before it, experiencing physically the tidal

4149
05:24:11,040 --> 05:24:15,600
tug of the amplitudes. He felt himself drawn back, then ahead, then back again.

4150
05:24:16,160 --> 05:24:21,680
Pedestrians clumped by, taking no notice. Obviously none of them saw what he saw.

4151
05:24:21,680 --> 05:24:28,480
They perceived neither archers, drugstore, nor the 1992 home art outlet. That mystified him most of all.

4152
05:24:29,600 --> 05:24:35,280
As the structure swung directly into its ancient phase, he stepped forward, crossed the threshold,

4153
05:24:35,280 --> 05:24:40,880
and entered archers drugstore. To the right, a long marble-topped counter.

4154
05:24:40,880 --> 05:24:46,800
Boxes on the shelves, dingy in color. The whole store had a black quality to it. Not merely in

4155
05:24:46,800 --> 05:24:52,400
regard to the absence of light, but rather a protective coloration, as if it had been constructed

4156
05:24:52,400 --> 05:24:59,920
to blend, to merge with shadows, to be, at all times, opaque. It had a heavy, dense quality.

4157
05:24:59,920 --> 05:25:04,880
It pulled him down, weighing on him like something installed permanently on his back.

4158
05:25:05,760 --> 05:25:10,720
And it had ceased to oscillate. At least for him, now that he had entered it.

4159
05:25:10,720 --> 05:25:15,920
He wondered if he had made the right choice. Now, too late, he considered the alternative,

4160
05:25:15,920 --> 05:25:22,080
what it might have meant, a return possibly to his own time. Out of this devolved world of

4161
05:25:22,080 --> 05:25:27,520
constantly declining, time-binding capacity. Out, perhaps, forever.

4162
05:25:28,480 --> 05:25:34,720
Well, he thought so it goes. He wandered about the drugstore, observing the brass and the wood,

4163
05:25:34,720 --> 05:25:39,040
evidently walnut. He came at last to the prescription window at the rear.

4164
05:25:39,840 --> 05:25:46,400
A wispy young man wearing a gray, many-button suit with vest appeared, and silently confronted him.

4165
05:25:47,040 --> 05:25:50,880
For a long time, Joe and the man looked at each other, neither speaking.

4166
05:25:50,880 --> 05:25:55,600
The only sound came from a wall-clock with Latin numerals on its round face.

4167
05:25:55,600 --> 05:26:01,680
Its pendulum ticked back and forth inexorably, after the fashion of clocks everywhere.

4168
05:26:03,040 --> 05:26:06,320
Joe said, I'd like a jar of ubeck.

4169
05:26:07,840 --> 05:26:13,680
The sal, the drugist said. His lips did not seem properly synchronized with his words.

4170
05:26:13,680 --> 05:26:16,720
First Joe saw the man's mouth open, the lips move,

4171
05:26:16,720 --> 05:26:19,440
and then after a measurable interval he heard the words.

4172
05:26:20,320 --> 05:26:24,000
Is it a sal, Joe said? I thought it was for internal use.

4173
05:26:24,240 --> 05:26:30,000
The drugist did not respond for an interval, as if a golf separated the two of them an epoch of time.

4174
05:26:30,000 --> 05:26:36,320
Then at last his mouth again opened, his lips again moved, and presently Joe heard words.

4175
05:26:37,200 --> 05:26:41,760
Ubeck has undergone many alterations as the manufacturer has improved it.

4176
05:26:41,760 --> 05:26:44,800
You may be familiar with the old ubeck rather than the new.

4177
05:26:45,600 --> 05:26:49,920
The drugist turned to one side, and his movement had a stop-action quality. He

4178
05:26:50,560 --> 05:26:56,560
flowed in a slow measured dance-like step, an aesthetically pleasing rhythm, but

4179
05:26:56,560 --> 05:27:02,000
emotionally jolting. We had had a great deal of difficulty obtaining ubeck of late,

4180
05:27:02,000 --> 05:27:07,920
he said, as he flowed back. In his right hand he held a flat-leaded tin, which he placed before

4181
05:27:07,920 --> 05:27:13,520
Joe on the prescription counter. This comes in the form of a powder to which you add coal tar.

4182
05:27:13,520 --> 05:27:18,880
The coal tar comes separate. I can supply that to you at very little cost. The ubeck powder,

4183
05:27:18,880 --> 05:27:25,680
however, is dear, forty dollars. What's in it, Joe asked. The price chilled him.

4184
05:27:26,480 --> 05:27:31,360
That is the manufacturer's secret. Joe picked up the sealed tin and held it to the light.

4185
05:27:32,080 --> 05:27:34,800
Is it all right if I read the label? Of course.

4186
05:27:35,920 --> 05:27:39,760
In the dim light entering from the street he at last managed to make out the printing

4187
05:27:39,760 --> 05:27:45,920
on the label of the tin. It continued the handwritten message on the traffic citation,

4188
05:27:45,920 --> 05:27:49,840
picking up at the exact point at which Runceter's writing had abruptly stopped.

4189
05:27:50,880 --> 05:27:57,360
Absolutely untrue. She did not repeat not try to use her talent following the bomb blast.

4190
05:27:57,360 --> 05:28:04,000
She did not try to restore Wendy Wright or Al Hammond or Edie Dorn. She's lying to you, Joe.

4191
05:28:04,640 --> 05:28:09,440
And that makes me rethink the whole situation. I'll let you know as soon as I come to a conclusion.

4192
05:28:10,240 --> 05:28:12,640
Meanwhile, be very careful.

4193
05:28:14,000 --> 05:28:20,320
By the way, ubeck powder is of universal healing value if directions for use are rigorously and

4194
05:28:20,320 --> 05:28:21,840
conscientiously followed.

4195
05:28:23,440 --> 05:28:27,920
Can I make you out a check? Joe asked the drugist. I don't have forty dollars with me,

4196
05:28:27,920 --> 05:28:32,400
and I need the ubeck badly. It's literally a matter hanging between life and death.

4197
05:28:32,960 --> 05:28:35,280
He reached into his jacket pocket for his checkbook.

4198
05:28:36,160 --> 05:28:40,720
You're not from Des Moines, are you? the drugist said. I can tell by your accent.

4199
05:28:42,000 --> 05:28:47,200
No, I'd have to know you to take a check that large. We've had a whole rash of bad checks

4200
05:28:47,200 --> 05:28:49,920
the last few weeks all by people from out of town.

4201
05:28:50,960 --> 05:28:56,400
Credit card, then? the drugist said. What is a credit card?

4202
05:28:58,320 --> 05:29:04,000
Laying down the tin of ubeck, Joe turned and walked wordlessly out of the drug store onto

4203
05:29:04,000 --> 05:29:08,880
the sidewalk. He crossed the street, starting in the direction of the hotel, then paused to

4204
05:29:08,880 --> 05:29:14,560
look back at the drug store. He saw only a dilapidated yellow building, curtains in its

4205
05:29:14,560 --> 05:29:20,640
upstairs windows, the ground floor boarded up and deserted. Through the spaces between the

4206
05:29:20,640 --> 05:29:25,920
boards he saw a gaping darkness, the cavity of a broken window, without life.

4207
05:29:26,560 --> 05:29:35,520
And that is that, he realized. The opportunity to buy a tin of ubeck powder is gone,

4208
05:29:35,520 --> 05:29:38,320
even if I were to find forty dollars lying on the pavement.

4209
05:29:39,520 --> 05:29:44,720
But he thought I did get the rest of Runciter's warning for what it's worth. It may not even

4210
05:29:44,720 --> 05:29:52,800
be true. It may be only a deformed and misguided opinion by a dying brain, or by a totally dead

4211
05:29:52,880 --> 05:29:59,280
brain, as in the case of the TV commercial. Christ, he said to himself dismally, suppose it is true.

4212
05:30:00,800 --> 05:30:04,400
Persons here and there on the sidewalk stared up, absorbitly, at the sky.

4213
05:30:05,360 --> 05:30:10,880
Noticing them, Joe looked up too. Chilling his eyes against the slanting shafts of sun,

4214
05:30:10,880 --> 05:30:17,120
he distinguished a dot exuding white trails of smoke, a high-flying monoplane industriously

4215
05:30:17,120 --> 05:30:23,520
sky-writing. As he and the other pedestrians watched, the already dissipating streamer spilled

4216
05:30:23,520 --> 05:30:32,320
out a message. Keep the old swisser up, Joe! Easy to say, Joe said to himself, easy enough to

4217
05:30:32,320 --> 05:30:39,200
write out in the form of words. Hunched over with uneasy gloom and the first faint intimations of

4218
05:30:39,200 --> 05:30:43,440
returning terror, he shuffled off in the direction of the Maramond Hotel.

4219
05:30:44,160 --> 05:30:49,040
Don Denny met him in the high-ceiling provincial crimson carpeted lobby.

4220
05:30:49,600 --> 05:30:55,440
We found her, he said. It's all over, for her, anyhow, and it wasn't pretty, not pretty at all.

4221
05:30:55,440 --> 05:31:00,720
Now Fred Zafke is gone. I thought it was in the other car, and they thought he went along with us.

4222
05:31:00,720 --> 05:31:04,160
Apparently he didn't get into either car. He must be back at the mortuary.

4223
05:31:04,720 --> 05:31:10,240
It's happening faster now, Joe said. He wondered how much difference Ubeck dangled

4224
05:31:10,240 --> 05:31:15,440
toward them again and again in countless different ways, but always out of reach would have made.

4225
05:31:15,440 --> 05:31:17,600
I guess we'll never know, he decided.

4226
05:31:18,640 --> 05:31:23,360
Can we get a drink here? he asked Don Denny. What about money, mine's worthless.

4227
05:31:24,000 --> 05:31:27,360
The mortuary's paying for everything, Rumseter's instructions to them.

4228
05:31:28,240 --> 05:31:33,360
The Hotel tab, too? It struck him as odd. How had that been managed?

4229
05:31:34,320 --> 05:31:39,040
I want you to look at the citation, he said to Don Denny, while no one else is with us.

4230
05:31:39,600 --> 05:31:43,600
He passed a slip of paper over to him. I have the rest of the message.

4231
05:31:43,600 --> 05:31:49,920
That's where I've been, getting it. Then he read the citation, then re-read it, then slowly

4232
05:31:49,920 --> 05:31:55,440
handed it back to Joe. Rumseter thinks Pat Connolly is lying, he said.

4233
05:31:56,160 --> 05:31:56,960
Yes, Joe said.

4234
05:31:57,920 --> 05:32:03,600
You realize what that would mean? His voice rose sharply. It means she could have nullified all

4235
05:32:03,600 --> 05:32:06,480
this, everything that's happened to her, starting with Rumseter's death.

4236
05:32:07,280 --> 05:32:09,840
Joe said it could mean more than that.

4237
05:32:10,880 --> 05:32:17,600
Eyeing him, Denny said, you're right. Yes, you're absolutely right. He looked startled,

4238
05:32:17,600 --> 05:32:23,680
and then acutely responsive, awareness glittered in his face of an unhappy, stricken kind.

4239
05:32:25,120 --> 05:32:30,560
I don't particularly like thinking about it, Joe said. I don't like anything about it. It's

4240
05:32:30,560 --> 05:32:35,520
worse, a lot worse than what I thought before, what Al Hammond believed, for example, which was

4241
05:32:35,520 --> 05:32:42,160
bad enough. But this could be it, Denny said. Throughout all that's been happening, Joe said,

4242
05:32:42,160 --> 05:32:46,000
I've kept trying to understand why. I was sure if I knew why.

4243
05:32:47,200 --> 05:32:52,480
But Al never thought of this, he said to himself. Both of us let it drop out of our minds for good

4244
05:32:52,480 --> 05:32:59,520
reason. Denny said, don't say anything to the rest of them. This may not be true, and even if it is,

4245
05:32:59,520 --> 05:33:01,040
knowing it, isn't going to help them.

4246
05:33:01,680 --> 05:33:07,440
Knowing what? Pat Conley said from behind them. What isn't going to help them?

4247
05:33:08,240 --> 05:33:11,840
She came around in front of them now, her black, color-saturated eyes,

4248
05:33:11,840 --> 05:33:14,240
wise and calm, serenely calm.

4249
05:33:15,680 --> 05:33:21,920
It's a shame about Edie Dorn, she said, and Fred Zafsky, I guess he's gone, too.

4250
05:33:22,800 --> 05:33:27,680
That doesn't really leave very many of us, does it? I wonder who'll be next?

4251
05:33:28,640 --> 05:33:31,840
She seemed undisturbed, totally in control of herself.

4252
05:33:32,720 --> 05:33:38,480
Tippi is lying down in her room. She didn't say she felt tired, but I think we must assume she is,

4253
05:33:38,480 --> 05:33:42,080
don't you agree? After a pause, Don Denny said,

4254
05:33:43,120 --> 05:33:44,320
Yes, I agree.

4255
05:33:45,440 --> 05:33:49,840
How did you make out with your citation, Joe? Pat said. She held out her hand.

4256
05:33:50,480 --> 05:33:56,960
Can I take a look at it? Joe passed it to her. The moment he thought has come.

4257
05:33:58,080 --> 05:34:02,960
Everything is now rolled up into the present into one instant.

4258
05:34:04,720 --> 05:34:09,360
How did the policeman know my name? Pat asked. After she had glanced over it,

4259
05:34:09,360 --> 05:34:13,760
she raised her eyes, looked intently at Joe, and then at Don Denny.

4260
05:34:14,560 --> 05:34:16,480
Why is there something here about me?

4261
05:34:18,320 --> 05:34:21,360
She doesn't recognize the writing, Joe said to himself,

4262
05:34:21,360 --> 05:34:24,240
because she's not familiar with it, as the rest of us are.

4263
05:34:24,400 --> 05:34:27,040
Runceter, he said.

4264
05:34:28,160 --> 05:34:33,600
You're doing it, aren't you, Pat? He said. It's you, your talent. We're here because of you.

4265
05:34:34,560 --> 05:34:39,120
And you're killing us off, Don Denny said to her, one by one. But why?

4266
05:34:40,000 --> 05:34:43,600
To Joe, he said, what reason could she have? She doesn't even know us, not really.

4267
05:34:44,640 --> 05:34:50,320
Is this why you came to Runceter Associates? Joe asked her. He tried but failed to keep his voice

4268
05:34:50,400 --> 05:34:54,640
steady. In his ears, it wavered and he felt abrupt contempt for himself.

4269
05:34:55,440 --> 05:35:00,640
Gigi Ashwood scouted you and brought you in. Was he working for Hollis? Is that it?

4270
05:35:01,200 --> 05:35:07,760
Is that what really happened to us? Not the bomb blast, but you? Pat smiled.

4271
05:35:09,040 --> 05:35:12,400
And the lobby of the hotel blew up in Joe Chip's face.

4272
05:35:15,840 --> 05:35:16,400
Thirteen.

4273
05:35:17,360 --> 05:35:23,040
Lift your arms and be all at once curvier. New extra-gentle

4274
05:35:23,040 --> 05:35:30,080
UBIC bra and long-line UBIC special bra mean lift your arms and be all at once curvier.

4275
05:35:30,080 --> 05:35:35,840
Supplies firm, relaxing support to bosom all day long, when fitted as directed.

4276
05:35:38,560 --> 05:35:44,240
Darkness hummed about him, clinging to him like coagulated damp warm wool.

4277
05:35:45,200 --> 05:35:50,400
The terror he had felt as intimation fused with the darkness became whole and real.

4278
05:35:51,120 --> 05:35:57,440
I wasn't careful, he realized. I didn't do what Runceter told me to do. I let her see the citation.

4279
05:35:59,360 --> 05:36:03,520
What's the matter, Joe? Don Denney's voice edged with great worry.

4280
05:36:03,520 --> 05:36:11,120
What's wrong? I'm okay. He could see a little now. The darkness had grown horizontal lines of gray,

4281
05:36:11,200 --> 05:36:20,400
as if it had begun to decompose. I just feel tired, he said, and realized how really tired

4282
05:36:20,400 --> 05:36:25,200
his body had become. He could not remember such fatigue never before in his life.

4283
05:36:26,240 --> 05:36:31,920
Don Denney said, Let me help you to a chair. Joe felt his hand clamped over his shoulder.

4284
05:36:31,920 --> 05:36:37,920
He felt Denney guiding him, and this made him afraid this need to be led. He pulled away.

4285
05:36:38,560 --> 05:36:45,520
I'm okay, he repeated. The shape of Denney had started to form near him. He concentrated on it,

4286
05:36:45,520 --> 05:36:50,400
then once again distinguished the turn of the century lobby with its ornate crystal chandelier

4287
05:36:50,400 --> 05:36:58,080
and its complicated yellow light. Let me sit down, he said, and groping found a cane-bottom chair.

4288
05:36:59,200 --> 05:37:02,640
To Pat, Don Denney said harshly, What did you do to him?

4289
05:37:03,600 --> 05:37:10,880
She didn't do anything to me, Joe said, trying to make his voice firm, but it dipped shrilly with

4290
05:37:10,880 --> 05:37:15,680
unnatural overtones as if it speeded up, he thought. High-pitched, not my own.

4291
05:37:16,480 --> 05:37:23,920
That's right, Pat said. I didn't do anything to him or to anybody else. Joe said, I want to

4292
05:37:23,920 --> 05:37:31,840
go upstairs and lie down. I'll get you a room, Don Denney said nervously. He hovered near Joe,

4293
05:37:31,840 --> 05:37:38,400
appearing and then disappearing as the lights of the lobby ebbed. The light waned into dull red,

4294
05:37:38,400 --> 05:37:45,120
then grew stronger, then waned once more. You stay there in that chair, Joe. I'll be right back.

4295
05:37:45,120 --> 05:37:48,400
Denney hurried off in the direction of the desk. Pat remained.

4296
05:37:49,600 --> 05:37:53,360
Anything I can do for you? Pat asked pleasantly.

4297
05:37:54,320 --> 05:38:02,080
No, he said. It took vast effort, saying the word aloud, it clung to the internal cavern lodged

4298
05:38:02,080 --> 05:38:05,440
in his heart, a hollowness which grew with each second.

4299
05:38:08,000 --> 05:38:15,200
Cigarette, maybe, he said, and saying the full sentence exhausted him. He felt his heart labor.

4300
05:38:15,200 --> 05:38:21,200
The difficult beating increased his burden. It was a further weight pressing down on him,

4301
05:38:21,280 --> 05:38:23,200
a huge hand squeezing.

4302
05:38:24,800 --> 05:38:30,720
Do you have one? he said, and managed to look up at her through the smoky red light,

4303
05:38:30,720 --> 05:38:34,160
the fitful flickering glow of an unrobust reality.

4304
05:38:34,960 --> 05:38:39,360
Sorry, Pat said. No, God. Joe said,

4305
05:38:40,800 --> 05:38:43,440
What's the matter with me?

4306
05:38:44,400 --> 05:38:46,640
Cardiac arrest, maybe, Pat said.

4307
05:38:47,840 --> 05:38:54,640
Do you think there's a hotel doctor? He managed to say. I doubt it.

4308
05:38:55,520 --> 05:39:04,080
You won't see. You won't look. Pat said, I think it's merely psychosomatic. You're not really sick.

4309
05:39:04,080 --> 05:39:04,800
You'll recover.

4310
05:39:05,920 --> 05:39:10,720
Returning, Don Denney said, I've got a room for you, Joe, on the second floor, room 203.

4311
05:39:11,440 --> 05:39:17,360
He paused and Joe felt his scrutiny, the concern of his gaze. Joe, you look awful.

4312
05:39:17,920 --> 05:39:23,280
Frail, like you're about to blow away. My God, Joe, you know what you look like.

4313
05:39:23,280 --> 05:39:25,760
You look like Edie Dorn looked when we found her.

4314
05:39:26,400 --> 05:39:33,040
Oh, nothing like that, Pat said. Edie Dorn is dead. Joe isn't dead. Are you, Joe?

4315
05:39:33,120 --> 05:39:40,960
Joe said, I want to go upstairs. I want to lie down.

4316
05:39:42,320 --> 05:39:48,080
Somehow he got to his feet. His heart, thudded, seemed to hesitate to not beat for a moment,

4317
05:39:48,080 --> 05:39:54,640
and then it resumed, slamming like an upright iron ingot, crashing against cement. Each pulse

4318
05:39:54,640 --> 05:40:00,160
of it made his whole body shudder. Where's the elevator? He said.

4319
05:40:00,880 --> 05:40:05,280
I'll lead you over to it, Denney said. Again, his hand clamped over Joe's shoulder.

4320
05:40:05,280 --> 05:40:09,120
You're like a feather, Denney said. What's happening to you, Joe?

4321
05:40:09,120 --> 05:40:11,680
Can you say? Do you know? Try to tell me.

4322
05:40:12,320 --> 05:40:18,400
He doesn't know, Pat said. I think he should have a doctor, Denney said, right away.

4323
05:40:19,440 --> 05:40:26,640
No, Joe said. Lying down will help me, he said to himself. He felt an oceanic pull,

4324
05:40:26,640 --> 05:40:34,000
an enormous tide tugging at him. It urged him to lie down. It compelled him toward one thing

4325
05:40:34,000 --> 05:40:40,560
alone, to stretch out on his back alone, upstairs in his hotel room, where no one could see him.

4326
05:40:41,120 --> 05:40:47,760
I have to get away, he said to himself. I've got to be by myself. Why? he wondered. He did not know.

4327
05:40:47,760 --> 05:40:52,960
It had invaded him as an instinct, non-rational, impossible to understand or explain.

4328
05:40:53,920 --> 05:40:58,080
I'll go get a doctor, Denney said. Pat, you stay here with him. Don't let him out of your sight.

4329
05:40:58,080 --> 05:41:04,720
I'll be back as soon as I can. He started off. Joe dimly saw his retreating form.

4330
05:41:04,720 --> 05:41:12,480
Denney appeared to shrink, to dwindle, and then he was entirely gone. Patricia Conley remained,

4331
05:41:12,480 --> 05:41:17,440
but that did not make him feel less alone. His isolation, in spite of her physical presence,

4332
05:41:17,520 --> 05:41:25,040
had become absolute. Well, Joe, she said, what do you want? What can I do for you? Just name it.

4333
05:41:26,080 --> 05:41:33,040
The elevator, he said. You want me to lead you over to the elevator? I'll be glad to.

4334
05:41:34,000 --> 05:41:38,320
She started off, and as best he could, he followed. It seemed to him that she walked

4335
05:41:38,320 --> 05:41:43,840
unusually fast. She did not wait, and she did not look back. He found it almost impossible to keep

4336
05:41:43,920 --> 05:41:50,960
her in sight. Is it my imagination, he asked himself, that she's moving so rapidly? It must be me.

4337
05:41:51,680 --> 05:41:58,400
I'm slowed down, compressed by gravity. His world had assumed the attribute of pure mass.

4338
05:41:58,400 --> 05:42:04,320
He perceived himself in one mode only, that of an object subjected to the pressure of weight,

4339
05:42:04,320 --> 05:42:09,120
one quality, one attribute, and one experience, inertia.

4340
05:42:10,080 --> 05:42:18,160
Not so fast, he said. He could not see her now. She had lightly trotted beyond his range of vision.

4341
05:42:18,800 --> 05:42:24,000
Standing there, not able to move any farther, he panted. He felt his face drip, and his eyes

4342
05:42:24,000 --> 05:42:31,760
sting from the salty moisture. Wait! he said. Pat reappeared. He distinguished her face as

4343
05:42:31,840 --> 05:42:39,440
she bent to peer at him. Her perfect and tranquil expression, the disinterestedness of her attention,

4344
05:42:39,440 --> 05:42:46,320
its scientific detachment. Want me to wipe your face? She asked. She brought out a handkerchief

4345
05:42:46,320 --> 05:42:50,640
small and dainty and lace edged. She smiled the same smile as before.

4346
05:42:51,920 --> 05:43:00,240
Just get me into the elevator! He compelled his body to move forward one step, two. Now he could

4347
05:43:00,320 --> 05:43:04,560
make out the elevator with several persons waiting for it, the old-fashioned dial above

4348
05:43:04,560 --> 05:43:11,040
the sliding doors with its clock hand, the hand, a baroque needle, wavered between three and four.

4349
05:43:11,040 --> 05:43:16,240
It retired to the left, reaching the three, then wavered between three and two.

4350
05:43:17,040 --> 05:43:22,320
It'll be here in a sec, Pat said. She got her cigarettes and lighter from her purse,

4351
05:43:22,320 --> 05:43:25,920
lit up, exhaled trails of gray smoke from her nostrils.

4352
05:43:26,880 --> 05:43:32,000
It's a very ancient kind of elevator, she said to him, her arms folded sedately.

4353
05:43:32,640 --> 05:43:39,120
You know what I think? I think it's one of those old open iron cages. Do they scare you?

4354
05:43:40,240 --> 05:43:47,360
The needle had passed, too. Now it hovered above one. Then plunge down firmly. The doors slid aside.

4355
05:43:48,480 --> 05:43:53,760
Joe saw the grill of the cage, the latticework. He saw the uniformed attendant seated on a stool,

4356
05:43:53,760 --> 05:43:55,680
his hand on the rotating control.

4357
05:43:56,560 --> 05:44:00,080
Going up, the attendant said. Move to the back, please.

4358
05:44:02,160 --> 05:44:04,960
I'm not going to get into it, Joe said.

4359
05:44:05,680 --> 05:44:11,440
Why not, Pat said? Do you think the cable will break? Is that what frightens you? I can see you're

4360
05:44:11,440 --> 05:44:16,480
frightened. This is what Al saw, he said.

4361
05:44:17,520 --> 05:44:22,160
Well, Joe, Pat said, the only other way up to your room is the stairs,

4362
05:44:22,160 --> 05:44:25,840
and you aren't going to be able to climb stairs, not in your condition.

4363
05:44:27,120 --> 05:44:35,040
I'll go up by the stairs. He started away, seeking to locate the stairs. I can't see,

4364
05:44:35,040 --> 05:44:40,640
he said to himself. I can't find them. The weight on him crushed his lungs, making it difficult and

4365
05:44:40,640 --> 05:44:46,960
painful to breathe. He had to halt, concentrating on, getting air into him, that alone. If it is a

4366
05:44:46,960 --> 05:44:53,120
heart attack, he thought. I can't go up the stairs, if it is. But the longing within him had grown

4367
05:44:53,120 --> 05:44:59,520
even greater. The overpowering need to be alone, locked in an empty room, entirely unwitnessed,

4368
05:44:59,520 --> 05:45:06,640
silent and supine, stretched out, not needing to speak, not needing to move, not required to cope

4369
05:45:06,640 --> 05:45:14,000
with anyone or any problem. And no one will even know where I am, he told himself. That seemed

4370
05:45:14,000 --> 05:45:21,520
unaccountably very important. He wanted to be unknown and invisible, to live unseen. Pat especially,

4371
05:45:21,520 --> 05:45:28,400
he thought, not her. She can't be near me. There we are, Pat said. She guided him, turning him

4372
05:45:28,400 --> 05:45:33,760
slightly to the left. Right in front of you, just take hold of the railing and go bump to

4373
05:45:33,760 --> 05:45:39,600
bump upstairs to bed. See? She ascended skillfully, dancing and twinkling,

4374
05:45:39,600 --> 05:45:43,120
poisoning herself, then scrambling weightlessly to the next step.

4375
05:45:43,120 --> 05:45:45,600
Can you make it? Joe said.

4376
05:45:46,560 --> 05:45:55,840
I don't want you to come with me. Oh, dear! She cluck-clucked with mocked dolefulness,

4377
05:45:55,840 --> 05:46:02,880
her black eyes shone. Are you afraid I'll take advantage of your condition? Do something to

4378
05:46:03,200 --> 05:46:13,440
you, something harmful? No, he shook his head. I just want to be alone.

4379
05:46:14,800 --> 05:46:19,840
Gripping the rail, he managed to pull himself up onto the first step, halting there. He gazed

4380
05:46:19,840 --> 05:46:24,880
up, trying to make out the top of the flight, trying to determine how far away it was, how many

4381
05:46:24,880 --> 05:46:32,160
steps he had left. Mr. Denny asked me to stay with you. I can read to you or get you things.

4382
05:46:32,160 --> 05:46:35,280
I can wait on you. He climbed another step.

4383
05:46:36,160 --> 05:46:43,680
Alone, he gasped. Pat said, may I watch you climb? I'd like to see how long it takes you,

4384
05:46:43,680 --> 05:46:51,200
assuming you make it at all. I'll make it! He placed his foot on the next step, gripped the railing,

4385
05:46:51,200 --> 05:46:56,400
and hoisted himself up. His swollen heart choked off his throat. He shut his eyes and

4386
05:46:56,400 --> 05:47:03,760
wheezed in strangled air. I wonder, Pat said, if this is what Wendy did. She was the first, right?

4387
05:47:04,560 --> 05:47:14,960
Joe gasped. I was in love with her. Oh, I know. Gigi Ashwood told me. He read your mind. Gigi and I

4388
05:47:14,960 --> 05:47:20,640
got to be very good friends. We spent a lot of time together. You might say we had an affair. Yes,

4389
05:47:20,720 --> 05:47:27,600
you could say that. Our theory, Joe said, was right. He took a deeper breath.

4390
05:47:29,120 --> 05:47:35,040
One. He succeeded in saying he ascended another step, and then with tremendous effort another.

4391
05:47:36,080 --> 05:47:44,480
That you and Gigi worked it out with Ray Hollis to infiltrate.

4392
05:47:45,120 --> 05:47:53,520
Quite right, Pat agreed. Our best inersals and Runciter wipe us all out. He made his way up one

4393
05:47:53,520 --> 05:48:02,000
more step. We're not in half-life. We're not— Oh, you can die, Pat said. You're not dead, not you in

4394
05:48:02,000 --> 05:48:08,080
particular, I mean, but you are dying off one by one. But why talk about it? Why bring it up again?

4395
05:48:08,640 --> 05:48:14,320
You said it all a little while ago, and frankly, you bore me going over it again and again.

4396
05:48:14,320 --> 05:48:20,480
You're really a very dull, pedantic person, Joe. Almost as dull as Wendy Wright. You two would have

4397
05:48:20,480 --> 05:48:28,880
made a good pair. That's why Wendy died first, he said, not because she had separated from the group,

4398
05:48:29,440 --> 05:48:37,120
but because— He cringed as the pain in his heart throbbed up violently. He had tried for another

4399
05:48:37,120 --> 05:48:42,000
step, but this time he had missed. He stumbled, then found himself seated, huddled, like—

4400
05:48:42,800 --> 05:48:49,200
Yes, he thought. Wendy, in the closet, huddled like this. Reaching out his hand, he took hold

4401
05:48:49,200 --> 05:48:56,480
of the sleeve of his coat. He tugged. The fabric tore, dried, and starved. The material parted

4402
05:48:56,480 --> 05:49:02,880
like cheap gray paper. It had no strength, like something fashioned by wasps. So there was no

4403
05:49:02,880 --> 05:49:08,400
doubt about it. He would soon be leaving a trail behind him, bits of crumbled cloth, a trail of

4404
05:49:08,400 --> 05:49:15,440
debris leading to a hotel room and yearn for isolation, his last laboured actions governed by

4405
05:49:15,440 --> 05:49:23,280
atropism, an orientation urging him toward death, decay, and non-being. A dismal alchemy controlled

4406
05:49:23,280 --> 05:49:31,040
him, culminating in the grave. He ascended another step. I'm going to make it, he realized. The force

4407
05:49:31,040 --> 05:49:36,720
goading me on is feasting on my body. That's why Wendy and Al and Edie—and undoubtedly,

4408
05:49:36,800 --> 05:49:42,560
Zafsky by now—deteriorated physically as they died, leaving only a discarded husk like

4409
05:49:42,560 --> 05:49:48,800
weightless shell containing nothing, no essence, no juices, no substantial density. The force

4410
05:49:48,800 --> 05:49:54,960
thrust itself against the weight of many gravities, and this is the cost, this using up of the waning

4411
05:49:54,960 --> 05:50:01,520
body. But the body, as a source supply, will be enough to get me up there. A biological necessity

4412
05:50:01,600 --> 05:50:06,800
is at work, and probably at this point not even Pat, who set it into motion, can abort it.

4413
05:50:07,440 --> 05:50:14,160
He wondered how she felt now as she watched him climb. Did she admire him? Did she feel contempt?

4414
05:50:14,720 --> 05:50:19,600
He raised his head, searched for her. He made her out, her vital face, with its several hues.

4415
05:50:20,320 --> 05:50:28,480
Only interest there. No malevolence, a neutral expression. He did not feel surprise. Pat had

4416
05:50:28,480 --> 05:50:33,280
made no move to hinder him and no move to help him. It seemed right, even to him.

4417
05:50:34,400 --> 05:50:36,240
Feel any better? Pat asked.

4418
05:50:37,360 --> 05:50:41,760
No, he said, and getting halfway up lunged onto the next step.

4419
05:50:42,960 --> 05:50:48,960
You look different, not so upset. Joe said, because I can make it. I know that.

4420
05:50:49,680 --> 05:50:51,600
It's not much further, Pat agreed.

4421
05:50:52,160 --> 05:50:59,680
Father, he corrected. You're incredible, so trivial, so small. Even in your own death spasms,

4422
05:51:00,720 --> 05:51:07,680
she corrected herself cat-like and clever. Or what probably seemed subjectively to you

4423
05:51:07,680 --> 05:51:12,800
as death spasms. I shouldn't have used that term, death spasms. It might depress you.

4424
05:51:12,800 --> 05:51:14,480
Try to be optimistic, OK?

4425
05:51:15,360 --> 05:51:19,040
Just tell me, he said. How many steps left?

4426
05:51:20,080 --> 05:51:24,880
Six. She slid away from him, gliding upward, noiselessly, effortlessly.

4427
05:51:25,440 --> 05:51:29,680
No, sorry, ten. Or is it nine? I think it's nine.

4428
05:51:30,800 --> 05:51:37,920
Again he climbed the step, then the next, and the next. He did not talk. He did not even try to see.

4429
05:51:37,920 --> 05:51:44,080
Going by the hardness of the surface against which he rested, he crept snail-like from step to step,

4430
05:51:44,080 --> 05:51:49,520
feeling a kind of skill develop in him, an ability to tell exactly how to exert himself,

4431
05:51:49,520 --> 05:51:52,400
how to use his nearly bankrupt power.

4432
05:51:53,120 --> 05:51:56,160
Almost there, Pat said cheerily from above him.

4433
05:51:56,800 --> 05:52:02,480
What do you have to say, Joe? Any comments on your great climb, the greatest climb in the history of

4434
05:52:02,480 --> 05:52:08,560
man? No, that's not true. Wendy and Al and Edie and Fred Zaske did it before you,

4435
05:52:08,560 --> 05:52:11,840
but this is the only one I've actually watched. Joe said,

4436
05:52:12,640 --> 05:52:19,840
Why me? I want to watch you, Joe, because of your low-class little scheme back in Zurich,

4437
05:52:19,840 --> 05:52:23,840
of having Wendy Wright spend the night with you in your hotel room.

4438
05:52:24,720 --> 05:52:28,320
Now, tonight, this will be different. You'll be alone.

4439
05:52:29,360 --> 05:52:33,360
That night, too, Joe said, I was. Alone.

4440
05:52:34,480 --> 05:52:40,320
Another step. He coughed convulsively, and out of him in drops hurled from his street face

4441
05:52:40,320 --> 05:52:47,680
his remaining capacity expelled itself uselessly. She was there, not in your bed,

4442
05:52:47,680 --> 05:52:52,800
but in the room somewhere. You slept through it, though, Pat laughed.

4443
05:52:53,520 --> 05:52:59,840
I'm trying, Joe said, not to cough. He made it up two more steps and knew that he had almost

4444
05:52:59,840 --> 05:53:04,480
reached the top. How long had he been on the stairs, he wondered, no way for him to tell.

4445
05:53:05,200 --> 05:53:09,280
He discovered then with a shock that he had become cold as well as exhausted.

4446
05:53:09,760 --> 05:53:15,760
When had this happened, he asked himself. Some time in the past it had infiltrated so

4447
05:53:15,760 --> 05:53:22,480
gradually that before now he had not noticed it. Oh, God! he said to himself and shivered frantically.

4448
05:53:22,480 --> 05:53:28,640
His bones seemed almost to quake. Worse than on Luna, far worse. Worse, too, than the chill

4449
05:53:28,640 --> 05:53:32,640
which had hung over his hotel room in Zurich. Those had been harbingers.

4450
05:53:33,360 --> 05:53:37,600
Metabolism, he reflected, is a burning process, an active furnace.

4451
05:53:37,600 --> 05:53:39,840
When it ceases to function, life is over.

4452
05:53:40,400 --> 05:53:46,240
They must be wrong about hell, he said to himself. Hell is cold. Everything there is cold.

4453
05:53:47,040 --> 05:53:54,480
The body means weight and heat. Now, weight is a force which I'm succumbing to, and heat.

4454
05:53:54,480 --> 05:53:59,920
My heat is slipping away, and unless I become reborn it will never return.

4455
05:54:00,560 --> 05:54:06,240
This is the destiny of the universe. So, at least I won't be alone.

4456
05:54:07,280 --> 05:54:13,680
But he felt alone. It's overtaking me too soon, he realized. The proper time hasn't come. Something

4457
05:54:13,680 --> 05:54:20,160
has hurried this up. Some conniving thing has accelerated it out of malice and curiosity.

4458
05:54:20,160 --> 05:54:26,880
A polymorphic, perverse agency which likes to watch an infantile, retarded entity which enjoys

4459
05:54:26,880 --> 05:54:32,400
what's happening. It has crushed me like a bent-legged insect, he said to himself.

4460
05:54:32,400 --> 05:54:37,920
A simple bug which does nothing but hug the earth, which can never fly or escape,

4461
05:54:37,920 --> 05:54:44,560
can only descend step by step into what is deranged and foul. Into the world of the tomb,

4462
05:54:44,560 --> 05:54:51,120
which a perverse entity surrounded by its own filth inhabits. The thing we call Pat.

4463
05:54:51,920 --> 05:54:55,120
Do you have your key? Pat asked, to your room?

4464
05:54:56,000 --> 05:55:01,680
Think how awful you'd feel to get up to the second floor and find you had lost your key

4465
05:55:01,680 --> 05:55:09,200
and couldn't get into your room. I have it! he groped in his pockets. His coat ripped away,

4466
05:55:09,200 --> 05:55:15,040
tattered, and in shreds it fell from him. And from its top pocket the key slid. It fell two steps

4467
05:55:15,040 --> 05:55:21,840
down below him beyond reach. Pat said briskly, I'll get it for you. Daring by him she scooped

4468
05:55:21,840 --> 05:55:27,760
up the key, held it to the light to examine it, then laid it at the top of the flight of stairs

4469
05:55:27,760 --> 05:55:33,280
on the railing. Right up here, she said, well you can reach it when you're through climbing.

4470
05:55:33,280 --> 05:55:40,240
Your reward. The room, I think, is to the left, about four doors down the hall. You'll have to

4471
05:55:40,240 --> 05:55:44,960
move slowly but it'll be a lot easier once you're off the stairs once you don't have to climb.

4472
05:55:45,040 --> 05:55:52,560
I can see, he said, the key and the top. I can see the top of the stairs.

4473
05:55:53,600 --> 05:55:58,960
With both arms grasping the banister he dragged himself upward, ascended three steps in one

4474
05:55:58,960 --> 05:56:05,920
agonizing expenditure of himself. He felt it deplete him. The weight on him grew, the cold

4475
05:56:06,000 --> 05:56:13,120
grew, and the substantiality of himself waned. But he had reached the top.

4476
05:56:14,160 --> 05:56:19,920
Goodbye, Joe. Pat said. She hovered over him kneeling slightly so that he could see her face.

4477
05:56:21,040 --> 05:56:27,760
You don't want Don Denney bursting into you. A doctor won't be able to help you. So I'll tell

4478
05:56:27,760 --> 05:56:33,120
him that I got the hotel people to call a cab and that you're on your way across town to a hospital.

4479
05:56:33,120 --> 05:56:37,360
That way you won't be bothered. You can be entirely by yourself. Do you agree?

4480
05:56:38,480 --> 05:56:46,160
Yes, he said. Here's the key. She pushed the cold metal thing into his hand, closed his fingers about

4481
05:56:46,160 --> 05:56:52,960
it. Keep your chin up, as they say here in 39. Don't take any wooden nickels, they say that too.

4482
05:56:54,320 --> 05:56:59,040
She slipped away then onto her feet. For an instant she stood there scrutinizing him.

4483
05:56:59,520 --> 05:57:03,200
And then she darted off down the hall to the elevator. He saw her press the button.

4484
05:57:03,200 --> 05:57:06,480
Wait. He saw the doors slide open, and then Pat disappeared.

4485
05:57:08,080 --> 05:57:13,120
Gripping the key he rose lurchingly to a crouched position, he balanced himself against the far

4486
05:57:13,120 --> 05:57:18,480
wall of the corridor, then turned to the left and began to walk step by step, still supporting

4487
05:57:18,480 --> 05:57:25,360
himself by means of the wall. Darkness, he thought. It isn't lit. He squeezed his eyes shut,

4488
05:57:25,360 --> 05:57:31,200
opened them, blinked. Sweat from his face still blinded him, still stung. He could not tell if

4489
05:57:31,200 --> 05:57:37,200
the corridor were genuinely dark or whether his power of sight was fading out. By the time he

4490
05:57:37,200 --> 05:57:41,520
reached the first door he had been reduced to crawling. He tilted his head up, sought for

4491
05:57:41,520 --> 05:57:48,320
the number on the door. No, not this one. He crept on. When he found the proper door he had to

4492
05:57:48,320 --> 05:57:54,080
stand direct, propped up to insert the key in the lock. The effort finished him. The key, still in

4493
05:57:54,080 --> 05:57:59,760
his hand, he fell. His head struck the door, and he flopped back onto the dust-choke carpet,

4494
05:57:59,760 --> 05:58:07,200
smelling the odor of age and wear and frigid death. I can't get in the room, he realized.

4495
05:58:07,200 --> 05:58:12,960
I can't stand up any more. But he had to. Out here he could be seen.

4496
05:58:14,000 --> 05:58:19,360
Gripping the knob with both hands he tugged himself onto his feet one more time. He rested

4497
05:58:19,360 --> 05:58:25,440
his weight entirely against the door as he tremblingly poked the key in the direction of the knob and

4498
05:58:25,440 --> 05:58:31,040
the lock. This way, once he had turned the key, the door would fall open and he would be inside.

4499
05:58:31,040 --> 05:58:36,080
And then he thought, if I can close the door after me and if I can get to the bed, it'll be over.

4500
05:58:37,200 --> 05:58:43,840
The lock grated. The metal unit hauled itself back. The door opened and he pitched forward, arms

4501
05:58:43,840 --> 05:58:49,600
extended. The floor rose toward him and he made out shapes in the carpet, swirls and designs,

4502
05:58:49,600 --> 05:58:55,360
and floral entities in red and gold, but worn into roughness and lusterlessness. The colors

4503
05:58:55,360 --> 05:59:00,720
had dimmed, and as he struck the floor feeling little, if any, pain, he thought, this is very

4504
05:59:00,720 --> 05:59:06,720
old, this room. When this place was first built they probably did use an open iron cage for an

4505
05:59:06,720 --> 05:59:12,000
elevator. So I saw the actual elevator, he said to himself, the authentic original one.

4506
05:59:13,920 --> 05:59:21,840
He lay for a time. And then as if called, summoned into motion stirred. He lifted himself up onto

4507
05:59:21,840 --> 05:59:29,760
his knees, placed his hands flat before him. My hands! He thought, good God! Parchment hands,

4508
05:59:29,760 --> 05:59:36,640
yellow and knobby, like the ass of a cooked, dried turkey, bristly skin, not like human skin,

4509
05:59:36,640 --> 05:59:43,360
pin feathers. As if I've devolved back millions of years to something that flies and coasts,

4510
05:59:43,360 --> 05:59:49,920
using its skin as a sail. Opening his eyes he searched for the bed, he strove to identify it,

4511
05:59:49,920 --> 05:59:55,920
the fat, far window, emitting gray light through its web of curtains, a vanity table ugly with

4512
05:59:55,920 --> 06:00:03,760
blank legs, then the bed with brass knobs capping its railed sides, bent and irregular as if years

4513
06:00:03,760 --> 06:00:10,320
of use had twisted the railing's warp of varnished wooden headboards. I want to get on it even so,

4514
06:00:10,320 --> 06:00:15,600
he said to himself. He reached toward it slid and dragged himself farther into the room,

4515
06:00:16,160 --> 06:00:25,360
and saw then a figure seated in an overstuffed chair facing him, a spectator who had made no sound,

4516
06:00:25,360 --> 06:00:27,920
but who now stood up and came rapidly toward him.

4517
06:00:29,040 --> 06:00:30,000
Glenn Runciter.

4518
06:00:31,120 --> 06:00:36,480
I couldn't help you climb the stairs, Runciter said, his heavy face stern. She would have seen me.

4519
06:00:36,480 --> 06:00:40,000
Matter of fact, I was afraid she'd come all the way into the room with you, and then we'd be

4520
06:00:40,000 --> 06:00:45,760
in trouble because she— He broke off, bent and hoisted Joe up to his feet as if Joe had no weight

4521
06:00:45,760 --> 06:00:52,160
left in him, no remaining material constituents. We'll talk about that later. Here. He carried Joe

4522
06:00:52,160 --> 06:00:56,400
under his arm across the room, not to the bed, but to the overstuffed chair in which he himself

4523
06:00:56,400 --> 06:01:01,440
had been sitting. Can you hold on a few seconds longer? Runciter asked. I want to shut and lock

4524
06:01:01,440 --> 06:01:08,000
the door in case she changes her mind. Yes, Joe said. Runciter strode in three big steps to the

4525
06:01:08,000 --> 06:01:13,200
door, slammed it and bolted it, came at once back to Joe. Opening a drawer of the vanity table,

4526
06:01:13,200 --> 06:01:18,320
he hastily brought out a spray can with bright stripes, balloons and lettering, glorifying

4527
06:01:18,320 --> 06:01:23,760
its shiny surfaces. You, Bic, Runciter said, he shook the can mightily, then stood before Joe,

4528
06:01:23,760 --> 06:01:30,720
aiming it at him. Don't thank me for this, he said, and sprayed prolongedly left and right.

4529
06:01:30,720 --> 06:01:35,280
The air flickered and shimmered as if bright particles of light had been released,

4530
06:01:35,360 --> 06:01:42,000
as if the sun's energy sparkled here in this worn out elderly hotel room. Feel better? It

4531
06:01:42,000 --> 06:01:48,320
should work on you right away. You should already be getting a reaction. He eyed Joe with anxiety.

4532
06:01:51,360 --> 06:01:58,560
14. It takes more than a bag to seal in food flavor. It takes UBIC plastic wrap,

4533
06:01:58,560 --> 06:02:05,680
actually four layers in one, keeps freshness in, air and moisture out. Watch this simulated test.

4534
06:02:07,440 --> 06:02:12,000
Do you have a cigarette, Joe said? His voice shook, but not from weariness,

4535
06:02:12,000 --> 06:02:18,480
nor from cold, both had gone. I'm tense, he said to himself, but I'm not dying. That process has

4536
06:02:18,480 --> 06:02:24,960
been stopped by the UBIC spray. As Runciter said it would, he remembered, in his take-TV commercial.

4537
06:02:25,680 --> 06:02:31,120
If I could find it, I would be all right, Runciter promised that. But he thought somberly it took

4538
06:02:31,120 --> 06:02:37,760
a long time, and I almost didn't get to it. No filter tips, Runciter said. They don't have

4539
06:02:37,760 --> 06:02:43,760
filtration devices on their cigarettes, and there's backward no good time, period. He held a pack of

4540
06:02:43,760 --> 06:02:50,800
camels toward Joe. I'll light it for you. He struck a match and extended it. It's fresh, Joe said.

4541
06:02:50,880 --> 06:02:54,960
Oh, hell yes! Christ, I just now bought it downstairs at the tobacco counter.

4542
06:02:55,600 --> 06:03:00,880
We're a long way into this. Well past the stage of clotted milk and stale cigarettes.

4543
06:03:01,440 --> 06:03:05,760
He grinned starkly, his eyes determined and bleak, reflecting no light.

4544
06:03:06,320 --> 06:03:11,680
In it, he said, not out of it. There's a difference. He lit a cigarette for himself, too.

4545
06:03:11,680 --> 06:03:15,440
Leaning back, he smoked in silence, his expression still grim.

4546
06:03:16,240 --> 06:03:21,280
And Joe decided tired, but not the kind of tiredness that he himself had undergone.

4547
06:03:22,160 --> 06:03:28,160
Joe said, Can you help the rest of the group? I have exactly one can of this, you big, most of it.

4548
06:03:28,160 --> 06:03:34,240
I had to use on you. He gestured with resentment, his fingers convulsed in a tremor of unresigned

4549
06:03:34,240 --> 06:03:38,640
anger. My ability to alter things here is limited. I've done what I could.

4550
06:03:39,600 --> 06:03:44,800
His head jerked as he raised his eyes to glare at Joe. I got through to you, all of you, every

4551
06:03:44,800 --> 06:03:50,720
chance I could, every way I could. I did everything that I had the capacity to bring about. Damn little,

4552
06:03:50,720 --> 06:03:55,280
almost nothing. He lapsed then into smoldering, brooding silence.

4553
06:03:56,560 --> 06:04:03,600
The graffiti on the bathroom walls, Joe said. You wrote that we were dead and you were alive.

4554
06:04:03,600 --> 06:04:08,320
I am alive, Runciter rasped. Are we dead, the rest of us?

4555
06:04:09,280 --> 06:04:15,520
After a long pause, Runciter said, Yes. But in the tape-TV commercial,

4556
06:04:15,520 --> 06:04:20,560
that was for the purpose of getting you to fight, to find Ubeck. It made you look and you kept on

4557
06:04:20,560 --> 06:04:26,640
looking too. I kept trying to get it to you, but you know what went wrong. She kept drawing

4558
06:04:26,640 --> 06:04:31,680
everyone into the past. She worked on us all with that talent of hers. Over and over again,

4559
06:04:31,680 --> 06:04:37,680
she regressed it and made it worthless. Runciter added, Except for the fragmentary notes I managed

4560
06:04:37,920 --> 06:04:43,120
to slip to you in conjunction with the stuff. Urgently, he pointed his heavy determined finger

4561
06:04:43,120 --> 06:04:48,000
at Joe, gesturing with vigor. Look what I've been up against. The same thing that got all of you,

4562
06:04:48,000 --> 06:04:53,280
that killed you off one by one. Frankly, it's amazing to me that I was able to do as much as I

4563
06:04:53,280 --> 06:04:59,680
could. Joe said, When did you figure out what was taking place? Did you always know from the start?

4564
06:05:00,720 --> 06:05:07,520
The start, Runciter said, Bitingly. What's that mean? It started months, or maybe even years

4565
06:05:07,520 --> 06:05:13,120
ago. God knows how long Hollis and Mick and Pat Connolly and S. Doe Melopon and G. G. Ash would

4566
06:05:13,120 --> 06:05:18,880
have been hatching it up, working it over and reworking it like Doe. Here's what happened.

4567
06:05:19,680 --> 06:05:25,280
We got lured to Luna. We let Pat Connolly come with us, a woman we didn't know, a talent we

4568
06:05:25,280 --> 06:05:31,360
didn't understand, but possibly even Hollis doesn't understand. An ability, anyhow, connected with

4569
06:05:31,360 --> 06:05:37,680
time reversion, not strictly speaking the ability to travel through time. For instance,

4570
06:05:37,680 --> 06:05:43,760
she can't go into the future. In a certain sense, she can't go into the past either. What she does,

4571
06:05:43,760 --> 06:05:50,160
as near as I can comprehend it, is start a counter process that uncovers the prior stages inherent

4572
06:05:50,160 --> 06:05:56,800
in configurations of matter. But you know that, you and Al figured it out. He ground his teeth

4573
06:05:56,800 --> 06:06:04,240
with wrath. Al Hammond, what a loss. But I couldn't do anything. I couldn't break through then,

4574
06:06:04,240 --> 06:06:12,240
as I've done now. Why were you able to now, Joe asked. Runciter said, Because this is as far back

4575
06:06:12,240 --> 06:06:18,720
as she is able to carry us. Normal forward flow has already resumed. We're again flowing from

4576
06:06:18,720 --> 06:06:24,880
past into present into future. She evidently stretched her ability to its limit. 1939, that's

